5476.jp Chronicle & Echo, Northampton \"Parents' plan may cause gridlock\" 21 January 2010, accessed 4 March 2010]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ccs.northants.sch.uk/ Official site]\n\n{{Schools in Northamptonshire}}\n\n[[Category:Academies in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Primary schools in Northamptonshire]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Northamptonshire]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c4:ad02:2001:eca2:9dc:9b3a:319c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caroline_Chisholm_School"}
{"title_page": "Patriots Day (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Patriots Day\n| image          = Patriots Day (film).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Berg]]\n| producers      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Scott Stuber]]\n* Dylan Clark\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* Stephen Levinson\n* Hutch Parker\n* Dorothy Aufiero\n* Michael Radutzky\n}}\n| screenplay = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Joshua Zetumer\n}}\n| story         = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Paul Tamasy\n* Eric Johnson\n}}\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]''|[[Casey Sherman]]<br />[[Dave Wedge]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Wahlberg\n* [[Kevin Bacon]]\n* [[John Goodman]]\n* [[J. K. Simmons]]\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Tobias A. Schliessler]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Colby Parker Jr.\n* Gabriel Fleming\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Closest to the Hole Productions\n* [[Bluegrass Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CBS Films]] (via [[Lionsgate]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|11|17|[[AFI Fest]]|2016|12|21|United States}}\n| runtime        = 133 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 132:59 --><ref name=\"BBFC\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film | title=''Patriots Day'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=December 14, 2016 | accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $45 million<ref name=\"BOM\" /> \n| gross          = $50.5 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=patriotsday.htm |title=Patriots Day (2016) |website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Patriots Day''''' is a 2016 American crime [[drama]] film about the [[Boston Marathon bombings]] and the subsequent terrorist manhunt. Directed by [[Peter Berg]] and written by Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer, the film is based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' by [[Casey Sherman]] and [[Dave Wedge]]. It stars [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Kevin Bacon]], [[John Goodman]], [[J.K. Simmons]], [[Michelle Monaghan]], and [[Alex Wolff]]. It marks the third collaboration between Berg and Wahlberg, following ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' and ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]''.\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[New York City]], and also filmed in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New Orleans]] and [[Philadelphia]]. The film premiered on November 17, 2016, at the [[AFI Fest]]. Distributed by [[CBS Films]] via [[Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>, ''Patriots Day'' was released in Boston, New York and Los Angeles on December 21, 2016, followed by a [[Wide release|nationwide expansion]] on January 13, 2017. The film was a box office disappointment, grossing just $50 million worldwide against a production budget of $45 million, but it also received many positive reviews for Berg's direction and the performances of its cast,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-patriots-day-review-20161216-story.html|title='Patriots Day' finds Mark Wahlberg and Peter Berg at their best in a fine tribute to the people of Boston|author=Kenneth Turan|date=20 December 2016|work=latimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> and was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] as one of the top ten films of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title=National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe title refers to [[Patriots' Day]], the Massachusetts state holiday on which the Boston Marathon is held.\n\n==Plot==\nOn April 14, 2013, Sergeant Tommy Saunders is capturing a suspect and failing to convince Commissioner Davis to let him off from a punishement duty the next day, working the [[Boston Marathon]]. During the marathon, brothers [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev|Dzhokhar]] and [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]] detonate two bombs, causing widespread panic. A young couple, Patrick Downes and Jessica Kensky, are injured and taken to separate hospitals, where they are both required to have their legs amputated. Steve Woolfenden, a family man, is also injured and separated from his toddler son, Leo, who is taken by the police to a safe location.\n\nFBI agent Richard DesLauriers is assigned to investigate the bombings in collaboration with  Boston police commissioner [[Ed Davis (police commissioner)|Ed Davis]], while Saunders searches for evidence and helps people that have been injured or separated from their loved ones in the chaos, including Patrick, Jessica, Steven and Leo. FBI analysts review footage of the bombing and identify Dzhokhar and Tamerlan as suspects, but DesLauriers is reluctant to release their pictures to the public without further evidence. His hand is forced when the pictures are leaked to the press, while Watertown Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese's men begin conducting door-to-door searches for the pair.\n\nDzhokhar and Tamerlan kill officer [[Sean Collier]] in a failed attempt to [[Theft|steal]] his pistol, and then carjack student Dun Meng, telling him of their plans to conduct another bombing in [[New York City]]. Just as Dzhokhar enters the [[Shell Gas]] station [[convenience store]], Meng escapes from the vehicle, and runs away fearfully to the [[Mobil]] Gas Station so that he can call the police; the brothers flee in the stolen car. Saunders arrives at the scene, learns of the brothers' plan and is given the stolen car's GPS tracking number, leading police to the pair, which leads to an armed confrontation. Several officers are injured in the ensuing shootout, where the brothers use both firearms and bombs. While Tamerlan is shooting, Pugliese fires at his ankle, wounding him and hindering his ability to gather more explosives. Tamerlan orders Dzhokhar to run to New York City to continue the rampage while he makes a last stand. As Tamerlan is subdued by the police, Dzhokhar runs over his brother in his flight, killing him as he escapes in the chaos.\n\nMeanwhile, Tamerlan's wife Katherine Russell and Dzhokhar's college friends are detained by the [[Hostage Rescue Team|FBI Hostage Rescue Team]] and questioned by the [[High-Value Interrogation Group]]. Russell refuses to disclose any knowledge of her husband's illegal activities, paraphrasing the Quran in defiance, while Dzhokhar's friends appear oblivious to his plans, despite having earlier found bomb components in his possessions. A local man named David Henneberry later finds Dzhokhar hiding under the sheets of his boat and calls the police. Dzhokhar is quickly surrounded and arrested after a brief standoff, as Saunders and his colleagues celebrate. The Boston police are invited to attend a [[Boston Red Sox]] game, where [[David Ortiz]] thanks them for their heroism and tells them to \"stay strong\".\n\nDzhokhar was convicted on thirty counts and sentenced to death by [[lethal injection]] and is currently waiting for his appeal in [[ADX Florence|federal prison]]; his three college friends were arrested for obstructing the bombing investigation and authorities are continuing to seek information regarding Russell's possible involvement in the bombings.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as [[Boston Police Department]] Sergeant Tommy Saunders \n* [[Kevin Bacon]] as Richard DesLauriers, Special Agent in Charge of the FBI Boston field office\n* [[John Goodman]] as Boston Police Commissioner [[Ed Davis (police commissioner)|Ed Davis]]<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\" />\n* [[J. K. Simmons]] as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese<ref name=\"Feb2016D\"/>\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]] as Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife and [[registered nurse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/synopsis|title=Official movie synopsis|publisher=|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MonaghanCast\"/>\n* [[Alex Wolff]] as [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* Themo Melikidze as [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* [[Michael Beach]] as [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]]<ref name=\"BeachCast\"/>\n* [[Vincent Curatola]] as [[Boston Mayor]] [[Thomas Menino]]<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\"/>\n* [[James Colby]] as Boston Police Superintendent [[William B. Evans|William Evans]]<ref name=\"ColbyCast\"/>\n* [[Jake Picking]] as [[MIT]] Officer Sean Collier, who was killed by the Tsarnaev brothers 79 hours after the bombings<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Melissa Benoist]] as Katherine Russell, Tamerlan Tsarnaev's widow<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n*[[Lana Condor]] as Li, Sean Collier's girlfriend and an MIT student\n* [[Jimmy O. Yang]] as Dun Meng ({{zh|c=\u5b5f\u76fe}}),<ref>Chinese name from: {{cite news|url=http://ny.uschinapress.com/weekends/2017/01-13/111620.html|title=\u300a\u7231\u56fd\u8005\u65e5\u300b\u4e0a\u6620 \u518d\u73b0\u6ce2\u9a6c\u7206\u70b8\u6848 \u7559\u5b66\u751f\u5b5f\u76fe\u4e8b\u8ff9\u642c...|newspaper=[[The China Press]]|date=2017-01-13|accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref> the driver the Tsarnaevs [[carjacked]] 80 hours after the bombing, who escaped at a gas station<ref name=\"YangCast\"/>\n* [[Christopher O'Shea]] as Patrick Downes, who lost his leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Rachel Brosnahan]] as Jessica Kensky, who lost her leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Khandi Alexander]] as Veronica the Interrogator<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Sean Avery]] as Watertown Officer on Franklin Street\n* [[David Ortiz]] as Himself\n* Cliff Moylan as Sergeant John MacLellan\n* Curtis J. Bellafiore as Officier Joey Reynolds\n* Token as Roommate \nThis film also includes a cameo appearance of the real Dun Meng inside the pizza restaurant in [[Malden, Massachusetts]], as well as the real David Henneberry, who was outside for a short time during the search for the bomber. [[Ken Casey]], singer and bassist for Boston punk band [[Dropkick Murphys]], also has a cameo as a man on a porch.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nThe film was one of what had originally been three proposed about the bombings, the other two being ''Boston Strong'' (based on [[Boston Strong (book)|the book of the same title]]), set to be directed by [[Daniel Espinosa]] and star [[Casey Affleck]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/boston-marathon-bombing-movie-boston-strong-rescued-by-fox/|title=Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Boston Strong' Rescued by Fox|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=November 18, 2014|website=TheWrap|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Stronger (film)|Stronger]]'', about bombing victim Jeff Bauman, starring [[Jake Gyllenhaal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-boston-marathon-bombing-stronger-exclusive-1201552624/|title=Jake Gyllenhaal Circles Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Stronger'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|website=Variety|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> It was to depict [[Edward F. Davis|Boston Police Commissioner Ed Davis]]' experiences during the manhunt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/01/media/60-minutes-movie-patriots-day/index.html|title=CBS to turn '60 Minutes' Segment into 'Patriots Day' Movie|first=Brian|last=Stelter|date=April 1, 2015|website=CNN Money|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> CBS Films purchased the rights to ''Boston Strong'' and merged it into the existing script.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2015/11/15/marathon-movies-patriots-day-and-boston-strong-join-forces/4l8jjHgzi3gnskkeBP1e1N/story.html|title=Movies on Marathon bombings are combined|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=November 15, 2015}}</ref> ''Stronger'' was made as a separate film, and released on September 22, 2017.\n\nOn March 31, 2015, [[CBS Films]] announced that it was producing the film as ''Patriots' Day'', depicting the 2013 [[Boston Marathon bombing]] and manhunt.<ref name=March2015Deadline>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|title=CBS Films Sets Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots' Day'; Mark Wahlberg Eyes Police Commish Ed Davis Role|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-police-commissioner-ed-davis-cbs-films-1201402219/|accessdate=April 4, 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2015}}</ref> The film's script was written by [[Matt Charman]], and focused on [[Boston Police Department|Boston Police Commissioner]] [[Edward F. Davis]].<ref name=\"March2015Deadline\" /> The film is also based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' and material from ''[[60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Busch|first=Anita|title=John Goodman Joins Boston Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/john-goodman-cast-bombing-movie-patriots-day-1201718895/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> Its final version, not focused specifically on Davis, was written by Peter Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer; [[Mark Wahlberg]] plays police officer Sgt. Tommy Saunders and [[Michelle Monaghan]] plays his wife, Carol.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\" /> Wahlberg produced the film along with [[Scott Stuber]], Dylan Clark, Stephen Levinson, Michael Radutzky, Hutch Parker, and Dorothy Aufiero.<ref name=\"BaconCast\" /> By February 2016, the title had dropped the apostrophe to become ''Patriots Day''.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> Also by then, [[J. K. Simmons]] had joined the cast as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] PD Sgt. Jeffrey Pugliese.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\">{{cite web|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=J.K. Simmons Joins Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/jk-simmons-patriots-day-movie-boston-marathon-bombing-1201709405/|accessdate=February 26, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCBS Films and [[Lionsgate]] co-financed the film, with Lionsgate also handling distribution.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> On March 8, 2016, [[Jimmy O. Yang]] joined the film's cast to play Dun Meng, who was carjacked by the Tsarnaev brothers.<ref name=\"YangCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Jimmy O. Yang Joins 'Patriots Day'; Sally Kirkland Cast In 'Most Hated Woman In America'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/jimmy-o-yang-patriots-day-sally-kirkland-most-hated-woman-in-america-1201716650/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cullen|first=Kevin|title=Responsibility worked against carjacking victim Dun Meng|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2015/03/12/the-argument-for-texting-and-driving/d88qK5BV2loEUQ4L7WlCOP/story.html|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 12, 2015}}</ref> On the same day, [[Vincent Curatola]] was cast to play the [[mayor of Boston]], [[Thomas Menino]], who was in office for his fifth term when the bombings took place.<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Vince Curatola Sworn In As Boston Mayor For 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/vince-curatola-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombinb-mayor-thomas-menino-1201726400/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> On March 11, 2016, John Goodman signed on to play former Boston Police Commissioner [[Edward F. Davis|Ed Davis]].<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\">{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=John Goodman Joins Mark Wahlberg in Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-goodman-joins-mark-wahlberg-874651|accessdate=March 12, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> On March 25, 2016, James Colby joined the film to play [[William B. Evans]], a Boston PD superintendent,<ref name=\"ColbyCast\">{{cite web|title=James Colby Joins Mark Wahlberg's Boston Marathon Bombing Drama, 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-colby-joins-mark-wahlbergs-878410|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> and following him, [[Michelle Monaghan]] also joined the film, to play Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Michelle Monaghan Joins 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/michelle-monaghan-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-1201727946/|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 29, 2016}}</ref> On March 31, [[Kevin Bacon]] joined the cast as FBI agent Rick Deslauriers,<ref name=\"BaconCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Kevin Bacon Joins 'Patriots Day' As Key FBI Agent|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/kevin-bacon-patriots-day-fbi-richard-deslauriers-special-agent-in-charge-1201729416/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> and on April 4, 2016, [[Alex Wolff]] and [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm6183987/bio  Themo Melikidze] were cast in the film as Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, responsible for the bombing and later manhunt.<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Alex Wolff, Themo Melikidze to Play Boston Marathon Bombers in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/alex-wolff-themo-melikidze-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-in-patriots-day-exclusive/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=TheWrap|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> [[Michael Beach]] later joined the film to play the [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]].<ref name=\"BeachCast\">{{cite web|last=McNary|first=Dave|title=Michael Beach to Play Gov. Deval Patrick in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/michael-beach-patriots-day-deval-patrick-1201745483/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=Variety|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2016, [[Rachel Brosnahan]] and Christopher O'Shea joined the film to play newlyweds Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who were at the finish line, and were both seriously injured but survived.<ref name=\"Apr2016D\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Rachel Brosnahan & Christopher O'Shea Join 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/patriots-day-rachel-brosnahan-christopher-oshea-cast-1201732976/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> The following day, [[Lana Condor]] was cast in the role of Sean Collier's prospective girlfriend.<ref name=\"CondorCast\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/x-men-actress-lana-condor-joins-patriots-day-1201748628/|title='X-Men' Actress Lana Condor Joins 'Patriots Day' (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, [[Melissa Benoist]] was cast in the film to play Katherine Russell, the widow of Tamerlan Tsarnaev, with [[Khandi Alexander]] set to play a law enforcement interrogator Veronica, [[Jake Picking]] as MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, who was killed 79 hours after the bombing.<ref name=\"May2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Melissa Benoist to Play Boston Marathon Bomber's Widow in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/supergirl-star-melissa-benoist-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-widow-in-patriots-day/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=May 5, 2016}}</ref> [[David Ortiz]], who retired from the [[Boston Red Sox]] after the [[2016 Major League Baseball season|2016 season]], appears as himself.<ref name=\"OrtizCast\">{{cite web|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|title=Red Sox Slugger David Ortiz to Re-enact Emotional Speech in Boston Bombing Movie (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/red-sox-slugger-david-ortiz-889462|accessdate=May 6, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Find out where Mark Wahlberg will be filming 'Patriots Day' in Massachusetts next week|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/24/64908/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Casting Company Seeks Extras For Boston Marathon Bombing Movie|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/03/02/patriots-day-mark-wahlberg-boston-marathon-bombings-casting-call/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=CBSLocal|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Patriots' Day', starring Mark Wahlberg, Open Casting Call will be held in Boston next weekend|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/05/patriotsdaycastingcall/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Tovia|title=Filming For Marathon Bombing Movie Stirs Emotions In Boston|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/03/25/471755112/-its-going-to-trigger-lot-of-ptsd-boston-prepares-for-marathon-bombing-film|accessdate=March 26, 2016|website=NPR|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> with production offices and a soundstage set up in one of the Centennial Park warehouses in [[Peabody, Massachusetts]].  All interior scenes at the FBI warehouse headquarters, as well as exterior 'command tent' scenes, were shot there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salemnews.com/news/local_news/patriots-day-film-company-takes-over-peabody-warehouse/article_0fac0837-787c-50df-a839-41a6f71154ab.html|title='Patriots' Day' film company takes over Peabody warehouse|first=Alan|last=Burke|website=Salem News|date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> Filming was previously scheduled to take place on Laurel Street in [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] to recreate the shootout that took place between police and the Tsarnaev brothers on the actual location, but after objections by residents, town officials denied permission for the film to be shot there.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Palma|first1=Kristi|last2=Hoover|first2=Amanda|title=Some Watertown residents object to film studio's plan to reenact Tsarnaev firefight|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/2016/02/23/movie-makers-want-recreate-the-watertown-shootout/eJkBEJldbiz6xsw0rFJNzK/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title='Patriot's Day' will not film Tsarnaev shootout scenes in Watertown|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/02/26/patriot-day-will-not-film-tsarnaev-shootout-scenes-watertown/mb7DDQku94i2xdyiotvdxI/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref> The City of [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] was approached to stand in for Laurel Street, and ended up with eight locations in the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://malden.wickedlocal.com/news/20161102/movie-shoots-are-mini-stimulus-packages-for-malden|title=Movie shoots are mini-stimulus packages for Malden|last=Leibowitz|first=Aaron|newspaper=Malden Observer|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref> The film crew then approached [[University of Massachusetts Dartmouth]] officials for permission to shoot some scenes at the campus, a request that was denied by its chancellor, Gerry Kavanaugh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Marathon filmmakers want to shoot at UMass Dartmouth|url=http://www.southcoasttoday.com/news/20160225/boston-marathon-filmmakers-want-to-shoot-at-umass-dartmouth|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=SouthCoastToday.com|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title=UMass Dartmouth won't allow 'Patriots' Day' to film on campus|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/03/05/umass-dartmouth-won-allow-patriots-day-film-campus/L2fPl6oPMn4jmYf4FBCCHM/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Simmons College]] stood in the place for exterior shots of UMass Dartmouth.\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where the Tsarnaev brothers killed MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, had allowed the film production to shoot \"entirely peaceful scenes\" on the campus for three days in June.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shanahan|first=Mark|title=Marathon bombing movie to film scenes at MIT|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/03/24/mit-says-patriots-day-director/jcdwKenTHRnCpyzQPMwJiO/story.html|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Letter to the MIT community regarding \"Patriots' Day\" filming|url=https://news.mit.edu/2016/letter-mit-community-regarding-patriots-day-filming-0324|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=MIT|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> Filming also took place at Collier's actual house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/04/05/patriots-day-scheduled-film-officer-sean-collier-former-residence/hxRsLUpvBuNxE0aSWotusK/story.html|title='Patriots Day' to film at Officer Sean Collier's former residence|first=Steve|last=Annear|website=Boston Globe|date=April 5, 2016}}</ref> The marathon finish line on [[Boylston Street]] was duplicated at the [[Naval Air Station South Weymouth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weymouth.wickedlocal.com/article/20160317/NEWS/160315938|title=PHOTOS: Movie set for \"Patriots' Day\" taking shape at SouthField in Weymouth|website=Wicked Local Weymouth|date=March 17, 2016}}</ref> in addition to scenes filmed at the actual finish line on the day of the 2016 marathon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/04/18/mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-scene-filming-boston-marathon-bombing-finish-line/|title=Mark Wahlberg Shoots 'Patriots Day' Scene At Boston Marathon Finish Line|website=CBSLocal|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> Dzhokhar's capture was filmed in [[Framingham, Massachusetts]] on its third anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/04/19/patriots-day-films-capture-scene-framingham/GUzKSWujVyW8sCSH9W9t5N/story.html|title='Patriots Day' films Tsarnaev capture scene in Framingham|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=April 19, 2016}}</ref> Additional filming was conducted at [[Doyle's Cafe]] in [[Jamaica Plain]] on April 14, 2016, [[Watertown, Massachusetts]] for shots of the police station and the sequence depicting Dun Meng escaping to the Mobil Gas station unlike the surveillance footage which was shot in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], and at [[Lasell College]] in [[Newton, Massachusetts]] on May 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaplainnews.com/2016/04/14/patriots-day-movie-filming-at-doyles-in-jp-today/18490|title='Patriots Day' Movie Filmed at Doyle's in JP Thursday|website=Jamaica Plain News|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newton.wickedlocal.com/photogallery/WL/20160519/NEWS/519009986/PH/1?refresh=true|title='Patriots Day' films in Newton|website=Wicked Local Newton|date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{Main|Patriots Day (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning composers and [[Nine Inch Nails]] members [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] were hired to write the musical score for the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots Day Score Coming from Trent Reznor & Atticus Ross|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/772391-trent-reznor-and-atticus-ross-composing-the-patriots-day-score#/slide/1|accessdate=October 2, 2016|website=ComingSoon.net|date=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Forever (2007 version)\" by [[Dropkick Murphys]] plays during the closing credits of the film; however, it is not included on the film's soundtrack.\n\n== Release ==\n''Patriots Day'' premiered on the closing night of the [[AFI Fest]] on November 17, 2016. It had a red carpet premiere at the [[Wang Theatre|Boch Centre Wang Theatre]] on December 14, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Globe article on Patriots Day premiere|url=https://www.boston.com/culture/entertainment/2016/12/15/the-patriots-day-red-carpet-was-filled-with-celebrities-survivors-and-heroes|accessdate=December 15, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref> The film was released in New York, Boston, Los Angeles, New Orleans, Philadelphia, Sofia, Bulgaria and Paris, France on December 21, 2016, followed by a wide release on January 13, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' Nabs Prime Awards Season Release|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wahlbergs-boston-bombing-movie-patriots-872420|accessdate=March 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Patriots Day'' grossed $31.9 million in the United States and Canada and $18.5 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $50.5 million, against a production budget of $45 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn North America, the film had its expansion alongside the openings of ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'', ''[[The Bye Bye Man]]'', and ''[[Sleepless (2017 film)|Sleepless]]'', as well as the wide expansions of ''[[Silence (2016 film)|Silence]]'' and ''[[Live by Night (film)|Live by Night]]'', and was expected to gross $18\u201320 million from 3,120 theaters in its four-day [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day|MLK]] opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-20170109-story.html |title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' and 'La La Land' to battle 'Hidden Figures' for box office win |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> It made $560,000 from Thursday night previews, less than the $860,000 made by Berg and Wahlberg's ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'' in September. The film ended up opening to $12.9 million (a four-day total of $14.2 million), finishing below expectations and 6th at the box office.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/patriots-day-sleepless-bye-bye-man-live-by-night-rogue-one-mlk-box-office-1201885490/|title=\u2018Hidden Figures\u2019 Stays Smart, But Why Are So Many Movies Bombing Over MLK Weekend? |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 80% based on 215 reviews, with an average rating of 6.8/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Patriots Day'' offers a stirring, solidly crafted tribute to the heroes of a real-life American tragedy without straying into exploitative action thriller territory.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/patriots_day_2016 |title=Patriots Day (2016) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 13, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 69 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/patriots-day |title=Patriots Day Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale,<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite tweet|user=CinemaScore|number=820147992464424960 |title=@realmonaghan @mark_wahlberg CONGRATULATIONS on your A+ #CinemaScore grade for @patriotsdayfilm http://www.cinemascore.com  |author=[[CinemaScore]] |date=January 13, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref> one of fewer than 90 films in the history of the service to receive such a score.\n\n{{expand section|date=August 2019}}\nKyle Smith of the ''[[New York Post]]'' called it: \"A great American movie about the greatness of ordinary Americans, Patriots Day combines an electrifying manhunt with the intimacy and feel for character writer-director Peter Berg showed in his brilliant TV series [[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|''Friday Night Lights]]''.\"<ref name=\"nypost\">{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |last1= Smith |first1= Kyle |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 brilliantly honors American heroes |url= https://nypost.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-brilliantly-honors-american-heroes/ |website= [[New York Post]] }}</ref>\n\nPeter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote: \"It\u2019s genuinely exciting megaplex entertainment, informed by extensive research, featuring bona fide movie stars, and staged with equal degrees of professionalism and respect.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=18 November 2016 |author= Peter Debruge |title= Film Review: \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 |url= https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/patriots-day-review-mark-wahlberg-1201921189/ |website= Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Reception from the Boston area===\nThough the film has mostly garnered approval among critics, many Boston-based publications criticized it for glamorizing the events it was based upon, and for the film's focus on Wahlberg's fictional character. In his review for ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', [[Ty Burr]] wrote: \"It\u2019s professionally made, slickly heartfelt, and is offered up as an act of civic healing. At best, it\u2019s unnecessary. At worst, it\u2019s vaguely insulting\", and when further referencing local moviegoer's reaction to Wahlberg's heroic but fictional Tommy Saunders character, he simply stated, \"We don\u2019t really want to see people who weren\u2019t there. Especially when they\u2019re everywhere\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2016/12/20/patriot-act-marathon-bombing-gets-hollywood-treatment/hy98c7gZs58MLoXmZtgbcJ/story.html|last=Burr|first=Ty |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 the Marathon bombing movie, is heartfelt and unnecessary |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners |accessdate=December 20, 2016|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', Boston-based critic Luke O'Neil also criticized Wahlberg's character, stating: \"For all his talk of honoring his people, Wahlberg seems content to rely on the most hackneyed of Masshole signifiers in their portrayal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a51733/patriots-day-review/ |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 Review |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=December 21, 2016 |last=O'Neil |first=Luke |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' gave the film a positive review.<ref>{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |author= James Verniere |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 captures the drama, horror of marathon attack |url= https://www.bostonherald.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-captures-the-drama-horror-of-marathon-attack/ |website= [[Boston Herald]] |accessdate= 2019-08-27 }}</ref>\n\nIn response Peter Berg stated that some people automatically disliked the film as they may have been in close proximity to the Boston bombings or they believed the film was made too quickly after the events had occurred.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> Katharine Q. Seelye, who was not from Boston, wrote in ''[[The New York Times]]'' that the Saunders character was \"[t]he biggest point of divergence\", as Boston-area residents disliked the [[composite character]]'s involvement in all the major events when he was not a single actual person, while people not from the Boston area \"may even appreciate [Saunders] as a narrative device\" and \"have not really questioned\" Saunders's role.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> She concluded \"that moviegoers outside New England pretty much accept the film on its own terms, as entertainment, and Bostonians do not.\"<ref name=\"Selyee\">{{cite news |date= 2017-01-13 |last= Selyee |first= Katharine Q. |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/13/movies/patriots-day-disconnect-between-bostonians-and-the-rest-of-us.html |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 Disconnect Between Bostonians and the Rest of Us |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |accessdate= 2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe [[National Board of Review Awards 2016|National Board of Review]] honored [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Peter Berg]] with their ''Spotlight Award'' for this film (and also for ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title= National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |work=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n*''[[Dark Night (2016 film)|Dark Night]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|4572514}}\n* {{AllMovie title|654626}}\n* [http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/patriots-day/ ''Patriots Day''] at ''[[History vs. Hollywood]]''\n\n{{Peter Berg}}\n{{Scott Stuber}}\n{{Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross}}\n{{Boston Athletic Association}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:CBS Films films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Thriller films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Crime films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Boston Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Berg]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Mark Wahlberg]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2013]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steve Jablonsky]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Atticus Ross]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Patriots Day\n| image          = Patriots Day (film).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Berg]]\n| producers      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Scott Stuber]]\n* Dylan Clark\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* Stephen Levinson\n* Hutch Parker\n* Dorothy Aufiero\n* Michael Radutzky\n}}\n| screenplay = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Joshua Zetumer\n}}\n| story         = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Paul Tamasy\n* Eric Johnson\n}}\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]''|[[Casey Sherman]]<br />[[Dave Wedge]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Wahlberg\n* [[Kevin Bacon]]\n* [[John Goodman]]\n* [[J. K. Simmons]]\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Tobias A. Schliessler]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Colby Parker Jr.\n* Gabriel Fleming\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Closest to the Hole Productions\n* [[Bluegrass Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CBS Films]] (via [[Lionsgate]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|11|17|[[AFI Fest]]|2016|12|21|United States}}\n| runtime        = 133 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 132:59 --><ref name=\"BBFC\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film | title=''Patriots Day'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=December 14, 2016 | accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $45 million<ref name=\"BOM\" /> \n| gross          = $50.5 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=patriotsday.htm |title=Patriots Day (2016) |website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Patriots Day''''' is a 2016 American crime [[drama]] film about the [[Boston Marathon bombings]] and the subsequent terrorist manhunt. Directed by [[Peter Berg]] and written by Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer, the film is based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' by [[Casey Sherman]] and [[Dave Wedge]]. It stars [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Kevin Bacon]], [[John Goodman]], [[J.K. Simmons]], [[Michelle Monaghan]], and [[Alex Wolff]]. It marks the third collaboration between Berg and Wahlberg, following ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' and ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]''.\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[New York City]], and also filmed in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New Orleans]] and [[Philadelphia]]. The film premiered on November 17, 2016, at the [[AFI Fest]]. Distributed by [[CBS Films]] via [[Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>, ''Patriots Day'' was released in Boston, New York and Los Angeles on December 21, 2016, followed by a [[Wide release|nationwide expansion]] on January 13, 2017. The film was a box office disappointment, grossing just $50 million worldwide against a production budget of $45 million, but it also received many positive reviews for Berg's direction and the performances of its cast,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-patriots-day-review-20161216-story.html|title='Patriots Day' finds Mark Wahlberg and Peter Berg at their best in a fine tribute to the people of Boston|author=Kenneth Turan|date=20 December 2016|work=latimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> and was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] as one of the top ten films of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title=National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe title refers to [[Patriots' Day]], the Massachusetts state holiday on which the Boston Marathon is held.\n\n==Plot==\nOn April 14, 2013, Sergeant Tommy Saunders is capturing a suspect and failing to convince Commissioner Davis to let him off from a punishement duty the next day, working the [[Boston Marathon]]. During the marathon, brothers [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev|Dzhokhar]] and [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]] detonate two bombs, causing widespread panic. A young couple, Patrick Downes and Jessica Kensky, are injured and taken to separate hospitals, where they are both required to have their legs amputated. Steve Woolfenden, a family man, is also injured and separated from his toddler son, Leo, who is taken by the police to a safe location.\n\nFBI agent Richard DesLauriers is assigned to investigate the bombings in collaboration with  Boston police commissioner [[Ed Davis (police commissioner)|Ed Davis]], while Saunders searches for evidence and helps people that have been injured or separated from their loved ones in the chaos, including Patrick, Jessica, Steven and Leo. FBI analysts review footage of the bombing and identify Dzhokhar and Tamerlan as suspects, but DesLauriers is reluctant to release their pictures to the public without further evidence. His hand is forced when the pictures are leaked to the press, while Watertown Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese's men begin conducting door-to-door searches for the pair.\n\nDzhokhar and Tamerlan kill officer [[Sean Collier]] in a failed attempt to [[steal]] his pistol, and then carjack student Dun Meng, telling him of their plans to conduct another bombing in [[New York City]]. Just as Dzhokhar enters the [[Shell Gas]] station [[convenience store]], Meng escapes from the vehicle, and runs away fearfully to the [[Mobil]] Gas Station so that he can call the police; the brothers flee in the stolen car. Saunders arrives at the scene, learns of the brothers' plan and is given the stolen car's GPS tracking number, leading police to the pair, which leads to an armed confrontation. Several officers are injured in the ensuing shootout, where the brothers use both firearms and bombs. While Tamerlan is shooting, Pugliese fires at his ankle, wounding him and hindering his ability to gather more explosives. Tamerlan orders Dzhokhar to run to New York City to continue the rampage while he makes a last stand. As Tamerlan is subdued by the police, Dzhokhar runs over his brother in his flight, killing him as he escapes in the chaos.\n\nMeanwhile, Tamerlan's wife Katherine Russell and Dzhokhar's college friends are detained by the [[Hostage Rescue Team|FBI Hostage Rescue Team]] and questioned by the [[High-Value Interrogation Group]]. Russell refuses to disclose any knowledge of her husband's illegal activities, paraphrasing the Quran in defiance, while Dzhokhar's friends appear oblivious to his plans, despite having earlier found bomb components in his possessions. A local man named David Henneberry later finds Dzhokhar hiding under the sheets of his boat and calls the police. Dzhokhar is quickly surrounded and arrested after a brief standoff, as Saunders and his colleagues celebrate. The Boston police are invited to attend a [[Boston Red Sox]] game, where [[David Ortiz]] thanks them for their heroism and tells them to \"stay strong\".\n\nDzhokhar was convicted on thirty counts and sentenced to death by [[lethal injection]] and is currently waiting for his appeal in [[ADX Florence|federal prison]]; his three college friends were arrested for obstructing the bombing investigation and authorities are continuing to seek information regarding Russell's possible involvement in the bombings.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as [[Boston Police Department]] Sergeant Tommy Saunders \n* [[Kevin Bacon]] as Richard DesLauriers, Special Agent in Charge of the FBI Boston field office\n* [[John Goodman]] as Boston Police Commissioner [[Ed Davis (police commissioner)|Ed Davis]]<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\" />\n* [[J. K. Simmons]] as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese<ref name=\"Feb2016D\"/>\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]] as Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife and [[registered nurse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/synopsis|title=Official movie synopsis|publisher=|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MonaghanCast\"/>\n* [[Alex Wolff]] as [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* Themo Melikidze as [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* [[Michael Beach]] as [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]]<ref name=\"BeachCast\"/>\n* [[Vincent Curatola]] as [[Boston Mayor]] [[Thomas Menino]]<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\"/>\n* [[James Colby]] as Boston Police Superintendent [[William B. Evans|William Evans]]<ref name=\"ColbyCast\"/>\n* [[Jake Picking]] as [[MIT]] Officer Sean Collier, who was killed by the Tsarnaev brothers 79 hours after the bombings<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Melissa Benoist]] as Katherine Russell, Tamerlan Tsarnaev's widow<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n*[[Lana Condor]] as Li, Sean Collier's girlfriend and an MIT student\n* [[Jimmy O. Yang]] as Dun Meng ({{zh|c=\u5b5f\u76fe}}),<ref>Chinese name from: {{cite news|url=http://ny.uschinapress.com/weekends/2017/01-13/111620.html|title=\u300a\u7231\u56fd\u8005\u65e5\u300b\u4e0a\u6620 \u518d\u73b0\u6ce2\u9a6c\u7206\u70b8\u6848 \u7559\u5b66\u751f\u5b5f\u76fe\u4e8b\u8ff9\u642c...|newspaper=[[The China Press]]|date=2017-01-13|accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref> the driver the Tsarnaevs [[carjacked]] 80 hours after the bombing, who escaped at a gas station<ref name=\"YangCast\"/>\n* [[Christopher O'Shea]] as Patrick Downes, who lost his leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Rachel Brosnahan]] as Jessica Kensky, who lost her leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Khandi Alexander]] as Veronica the Interrogator<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Sean Avery]] as Watertown Officer on Franklin Street\n* [[David Ortiz]] as Himself\n* Cliff Moylan as Sergeant John MacLellan\n* Curtis J. Bellafiore as Officier Joey Reynolds\n* Token as Roommate \nThis film also includes a cameo appearance of the real Dun Meng inside the pizza restaurant in [[Malden, Massachusetts]], as well as the real David Henneberry, who was outside for a short time during the search for the bomber. [[Ken Casey]], singer and bassist for Boston punk band [[Dropkick Murphys]], also has a cameo as a man on a porch.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nThe film was one of what had originally been three proposed about the bombings, the other two being ''Boston Strong'' (based on [[Boston Strong (book)|the book of the same title]]), set to be directed by [[Daniel Espinosa]] and star [[Casey Affleck]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/boston-marathon-bombing-movie-boston-strong-rescued-by-fox/|title=Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Boston Strong' Rescued by Fox|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=November 18, 2014|website=TheWrap|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Stronger (film)|Stronger]]'', about bombing victim Jeff Bauman, starring [[Jake Gyllenhaal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-boston-marathon-bombing-stronger-exclusive-1201552624/|title=Jake Gyllenhaal Circles Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Stronger'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|website=Variety|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> It was to depict [[Edward F. Davis|Boston Police Commissioner Ed Davis]]' experiences during the manhunt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/01/media/60-minutes-movie-patriots-day/index.html|title=CBS to turn '60 Minutes' Segment into 'Patriots Day' Movie|first=Brian|last=Stelter|date=April 1, 2015|website=CNN Money|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> CBS Films purchased the rights to ''Boston Strong'' and merged it into the existing script.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2015/11/15/marathon-movies-patriots-day-and-boston-strong-join-forces/4l8jjHgzi3gnskkeBP1e1N/story.html|title=Movies on Marathon bombings are combined|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=November 15, 2015}}</ref> ''Stronger'' was made as a separate film, and released on September 22, 2017.\n\nOn March 31, 2015, [[CBS Films]] announced that it was producing the film as ''Patriots' Day'', depicting the 2013 [[Boston Marathon bombing]] and manhunt.<ref name=March2015Deadline>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|title=CBS Films Sets Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots' Day'; Mark Wahlberg Eyes Police Commish Ed Davis Role|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-police-commissioner-ed-davis-cbs-films-1201402219/|accessdate=April 4, 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2015}}</ref> The film's script was written by [[Matt Charman]], and focused on [[Boston Police Department|Boston Police Commissioner]] [[Edward F. Davis]].<ref name=\"March2015Deadline\" /> The film is also based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' and material from ''[[60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Busch|first=Anita|title=John Goodman Joins Boston Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/john-goodman-cast-bombing-movie-patriots-day-1201718895/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> Its final version, not focused specifically on Davis, was written by Peter Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer; [[Mark Wahlberg]] plays police officer Sgt. Tommy Saunders and [[Michelle Monaghan]] plays his wife, Carol.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\" /> Wahlberg produced the film along with [[Scott Stuber]], Dylan Clark, Stephen Levinson, Michael Radutzky, Hutch Parker, and Dorothy Aufiero.<ref name=\"BaconCast\" /> By February 2016, the title had dropped the apostrophe to become ''Patriots Day''.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> Also by then, [[J. K. Simmons]] had joined the cast as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] PD Sgt. Jeffrey Pugliese.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\">{{cite web|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=J.K. Simmons Joins Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/jk-simmons-patriots-day-movie-boston-marathon-bombing-1201709405/|accessdate=February 26, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCBS Films and [[Lionsgate]] co-financed the film, with Lionsgate also handling distribution.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> On March 8, 2016, [[Jimmy O. Yang]] joined the film's cast to play Dun Meng, who was carjacked by the Tsarnaev brothers.<ref name=\"YangCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Jimmy O. Yang Joins 'Patriots Day'; Sally Kirkland Cast In 'Most Hated Woman In America'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/jimmy-o-yang-patriots-day-sally-kirkland-most-hated-woman-in-america-1201716650/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cullen|first=Kevin|title=Responsibility worked against carjacking victim Dun Meng|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2015/03/12/the-argument-for-texting-and-driving/d88qK5BV2loEUQ4L7WlCOP/story.html|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 12, 2015}}</ref> On the same day, [[Vincent Curatola]] was cast to play the [[mayor of Boston]], [[Thomas Menino]], who was in office for his fifth term when the bombings took place.<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Vince Curatola Sworn In As Boston Mayor For 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/vince-curatola-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombinb-mayor-thomas-menino-1201726400/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> On March 11, 2016, John Goodman signed on to play former Boston Police Commissioner [[Edward F. Davis|Ed Davis]].<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\">{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=John Goodman Joins Mark Wahlberg in Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-goodman-joins-mark-wahlberg-874651|accessdate=March 12, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> On March 25, 2016, James Colby joined the film to play [[William B. Evans]], a Boston PD superintendent,<ref name=\"ColbyCast\">{{cite web|title=James Colby Joins Mark Wahlberg's Boston Marathon Bombing Drama, 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-colby-joins-mark-wahlbergs-878410|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> and following him, [[Michelle Monaghan]] also joined the film, to play Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Michelle Monaghan Joins 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/michelle-monaghan-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-1201727946/|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 29, 2016}}</ref> On March 31, [[Kevin Bacon]] joined the cast as FBI agent Rick Deslauriers,<ref name=\"BaconCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Kevin Bacon Joins 'Patriots Day' As Key FBI Agent|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/kevin-bacon-patriots-day-fbi-richard-deslauriers-special-agent-in-charge-1201729416/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> and on April 4, 2016, [[Alex Wolff]] and [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm6183987/bio  Themo Melikidze] were cast in the film as Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, responsible for the bombing and later manhunt.<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Alex Wolff, Themo Melikidze to Play Boston Marathon Bombers in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/alex-wolff-themo-melikidze-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-in-patriots-day-exclusive/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=TheWrap|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> [[Michael Beach]] later joined the film to play the [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]].<ref name=\"BeachCast\">{{cite web|last=McNary|first=Dave|title=Michael Beach to Play Gov. Deval Patrick in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/michael-beach-patriots-day-deval-patrick-1201745483/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=Variety|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2016, [[Rachel Brosnahan]] and Christopher O'Shea joined the film to play newlyweds Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who were at the finish line, and were both seriously injured but survived.<ref name=\"Apr2016D\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Rachel Brosnahan & Christopher O'Shea Join 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/patriots-day-rachel-brosnahan-christopher-oshea-cast-1201732976/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> The following day, [[Lana Condor]] was cast in the role of Sean Collier's prospective girlfriend.<ref name=\"CondorCast\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/x-men-actress-lana-condor-joins-patriots-day-1201748628/|title='X-Men' Actress Lana Condor Joins 'Patriots Day' (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, [[Melissa Benoist]] was cast in the film to play Katherine Russell, the widow of Tamerlan Tsarnaev, with [[Khandi Alexander]] set to play a law enforcement interrogator Veronica, [[Jake Picking]] as MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, who was killed 79 hours after the bombing.<ref name=\"May2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Melissa Benoist to Play Boston Marathon Bomber's Widow in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/supergirl-star-melissa-benoist-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-widow-in-patriots-day/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=May 5, 2016}}</ref> [[David Ortiz]], who retired from the [[Boston Red Sox]] after the [[2016 Major League Baseball season|2016 season]], appears as himself.<ref name=\"OrtizCast\">{{cite web|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|title=Red Sox Slugger David Ortiz to Re-enact Emotional Speech in Boston Bombing Movie (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/red-sox-slugger-david-ortiz-889462|accessdate=May 6, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Find out where Mark Wahlberg will be filming 'Patriots Day' in Massachusetts next week|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/24/64908/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Casting Company Seeks Extras For Boston Marathon Bombing Movie|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/03/02/patriots-day-mark-wahlberg-boston-marathon-bombings-casting-call/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=CBSLocal|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Patriots' Day', starring Mark Wahlberg, Open Casting Call will be held in Boston next weekend|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/05/patriotsdaycastingcall/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Tovia|title=Filming For Marathon Bombing Movie Stirs Emotions In Boston|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/03/25/471755112/-its-going-to-trigger-lot-of-ptsd-boston-prepares-for-marathon-bombing-film|accessdate=March 26, 2016|website=NPR|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> with production offices and a soundstage set up in one of the Centennial Park warehouses in [[Peabody, Massachusetts]].  All interior scenes at the FBI warehouse headquarters, as well as exterior 'command tent' scenes, were shot there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salemnews.com/news/local_news/patriots-day-film-company-takes-over-peabody-warehouse/article_0fac0837-787c-50df-a839-41a6f71154ab.html|title='Patriots' Day' film company takes over Peabody warehouse|first=Alan|last=Burke|website=Salem News|date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> Filming was previously scheduled to take place on Laurel Street in [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] to recreate the shootout that took place between police and the Tsarnaev brothers on the actual location, but after objections by residents, town officials denied permission for the film to be shot there.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Palma|first1=Kristi|last2=Hoover|first2=Amanda|title=Some Watertown residents object to film studio's plan to reenact Tsarnaev firefight|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/2016/02/23/movie-makers-want-recreate-the-watertown-shootout/eJkBEJldbiz6xsw0rFJNzK/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title='Patriot's Day' will not film Tsarnaev shootout scenes in Watertown|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/02/26/patriot-day-will-not-film-tsarnaev-shootout-scenes-watertown/mb7DDQku94i2xdyiotvdxI/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref> The City of [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] was approached to stand in for Laurel Street, and ended up with eight locations in the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://malden.wickedlocal.com/news/20161102/movie-shoots-are-mini-stimulus-packages-for-malden|title=Movie shoots are mini-stimulus packages for Malden|last=Leibowitz|first=Aaron|newspaper=Malden Observer|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref> The film crew then approached [[University of Massachusetts Dartmouth]] officials for permission to shoot some scenes at the campus, a request that was denied by its chancellor, Gerry Kavanaugh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Marathon filmmakers want to shoot at UMass Dartmouth|url=http://www.southcoasttoday.com/news/20160225/boston-marathon-filmmakers-want-to-shoot-at-umass-dartmouth|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=SouthCoastToday.com|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title=UMass Dartmouth won't allow 'Patriots' Day' to film on campus|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/03/05/umass-dartmouth-won-allow-patriots-day-film-campus/L2fPl6oPMn4jmYf4FBCCHM/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Simmons College]] stood in the place for exterior shots of UMass Dartmouth.\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where the Tsarnaev brothers killed MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, had allowed the film production to shoot \"entirely peaceful scenes\" on the campus for three days in June.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shanahan|first=Mark|title=Marathon bombing movie to film scenes at MIT|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/03/24/mit-says-patriots-day-director/jcdwKenTHRnCpyzQPMwJiO/story.html|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Letter to the MIT community regarding \"Patriots' Day\" filming|url=https://news.mit.edu/2016/letter-mit-community-regarding-patriots-day-filming-0324|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=MIT|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> Filming also took place at Collier's actual house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/04/05/patriots-day-scheduled-film-officer-sean-collier-former-residence/hxRsLUpvBuNxE0aSWotusK/story.html|title='Patriots Day' to film at Officer Sean Collier's former residence|first=Steve|last=Annear|website=Boston Globe|date=April 5, 2016}}</ref> The marathon finish line on [[Boylston Street]] was duplicated at the [[Naval Air Station South Weymouth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weymouth.wickedlocal.com/article/20160317/NEWS/160315938|title=PHOTOS: Movie set for \"Patriots' Day\" taking shape at SouthField in Weymouth|website=Wicked Local Weymouth|date=March 17, 2016}}</ref> in addition to scenes filmed at the actual finish line on the day of the 2016 marathon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/04/18/mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-scene-filming-boston-marathon-bombing-finish-line/|title=Mark Wahlberg Shoots 'Patriots Day' Scene At Boston Marathon Finish Line|website=CBSLocal|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> Dzhokhar's capture was filmed in [[Framingham, Massachusetts]] on its third anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/04/19/patriots-day-films-capture-scene-framingham/GUzKSWujVyW8sCSH9W9t5N/story.html|title='Patriots Day' films Tsarnaev capture scene in Framingham|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=April 19, 2016}}</ref> Additional filming was conducted at [[Doyle's Cafe]] in [[Jamaica Plain]] on April 14, 2016, [[Watertown, Massachusetts]] for shots of the police station and the sequence depicting Dun Meng escaping to the Mobil Gas station unlike the surveillance footage which was shot in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], and at [[Lasell College]] in [[Newton, Massachusetts]] on May 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaplainnews.com/2016/04/14/patriots-day-movie-filming-at-doyles-in-jp-today/18490|title='Patriots Day' Movie Filmed at Doyle's in JP Thursday|website=Jamaica Plain News|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newton.wickedlocal.com/photogallery/WL/20160519/NEWS/519009986/PH/1?refresh=true|title='Patriots Day' films in Newton|website=Wicked Local Newton|date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{Main|Patriots Day (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning composers and [[Nine Inch Nails]] members [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] were hired to write the musical score for the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots Day Score Coming from Trent Reznor & Atticus Ross|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/772391-trent-reznor-and-atticus-ross-composing-the-patriots-day-score#/slide/1|accessdate=October 2, 2016|website=ComingSoon.net|date=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Forever (2007 version)\" by [[Dropkick Murphys]] plays during the closing credits of the film; however, it is not included on the film's soundtrack.\n\n== Release ==\n''Patriots Day'' premiered on the closing night of the [[AFI Fest]] on November 17, 2016. It had a red carpet premiere at the [[Wang Theatre|Boch Centre Wang Theatre]] on December 14, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Globe article on Patriots Day premiere|url=https://www.boston.com/culture/entertainment/2016/12/15/the-patriots-day-red-carpet-was-filled-with-celebrities-survivors-and-heroes|accessdate=December 15, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref> The film was released in New York, Boston, Los Angeles, New Orleans, Philadelphia, Sofia, Bulgaria and Paris, France on December 21, 2016, followed by a wide release on January 13, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' Nabs Prime Awards Season Release|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wahlbergs-boston-bombing-movie-patriots-872420|accessdate=March 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Patriots Day'' grossed $31.9 million in the United States and Canada and $18.5 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $50.5 million, against a production budget of $45 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn North America, the film had its expansion alongside the openings of ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'', ''[[The Bye Bye Man]]'', and ''[[Sleepless (2017 film)|Sleepless]]'', as well as the wide expansions of ''[[Silence (2016 film)|Silence]]'' and ''[[Live by Night (film)|Live by Night]]'', and was expected to gross $18\u201320 million from 3,120 theaters in its four-day [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day|MLK]] opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-20170109-story.html |title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' and 'La La Land' to battle 'Hidden Figures' for box office win |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> It made $560,000 from Thursday night previews, less than the $860,000 made by Berg and Wahlberg's ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'' in September. The film ended up opening to $12.9 million (a four-day total of $14.2 million), finishing below expectations and 6th at the box office.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/patriots-day-sleepless-bye-bye-man-live-by-night-rogue-one-mlk-box-office-1201885490/|title=\u2018Hidden Figures\u2019 Stays Smart, But Why Are So Many Movies Bombing Over MLK Weekend? |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 80% based on 215 reviews, with an average rating of 6.8/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Patriots Day'' offers a stirring, solidly crafted tribute to the heroes of a real-life American tragedy without straying into exploitative action thriller territory.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/patriots_day_2016 |title=Patriots Day (2016) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 13, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 69 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/patriots-day |title=Patriots Day Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale,<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite tweet|user=CinemaScore|number=820147992464424960 |title=@realmonaghan @mark_wahlberg CONGRATULATIONS on your A+ #CinemaScore grade for @patriotsdayfilm http://www.cinemascore.com  |author=[[CinemaScore]] |date=January 13, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref> one of fewer than 90 films in the history of the service to receive such a score.\n\n{{expand section|date=August 2019}}\nKyle Smith of the ''[[New York Post]]'' called it: \"A great American movie about the greatness of ordinary Americans, Patriots Day combines an electrifying manhunt with the intimacy and feel for character writer-director Peter Berg showed in his brilliant TV series [[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|''Friday Night Lights]]''.\"<ref name=\"nypost\">{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |last1= Smith |first1= Kyle |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 brilliantly honors American heroes |url= https://nypost.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-brilliantly-honors-american-heroes/ |website= [[New York Post]] }}</ref>\n\nPeter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote: \"It\u2019s genuinely exciting megaplex entertainment, informed by extensive research, featuring bona fide movie stars, and staged with equal degrees of professionalism and respect.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=18 November 2016 |author= Peter Debruge |title= Film Review: \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 |url= https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/patriots-day-review-mark-wahlberg-1201921189/ |website= Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Reception from the Boston area===\nThough the film has mostly garnered approval among critics, many Boston-based publications criticized it for glamorizing the events it was based upon, and for the film's focus on Wahlberg's fictional character. In his review for ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', [[Ty Burr]] wrote: \"It\u2019s professionally made, slickly heartfelt, and is offered up as an act of civic healing. At best, it\u2019s unnecessary. At worst, it\u2019s vaguely insulting\", and when further referencing local moviegoer's reaction to Wahlberg's heroic but fictional Tommy Saunders character, he simply stated, \"We don\u2019t really want to see people who weren\u2019t there. Especially when they\u2019re everywhere\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2016/12/20/patriot-act-marathon-bombing-gets-hollywood-treatment/hy98c7gZs58MLoXmZtgbcJ/story.html|last=Burr|first=Ty |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 the Marathon bombing movie, is heartfelt and unnecessary |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners |accessdate=December 20, 2016|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', Boston-based critic Luke O'Neil also criticized Wahlberg's character, stating: \"For all his talk of honoring his people, Wahlberg seems content to rely on the most hackneyed of Masshole signifiers in their portrayal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a51733/patriots-day-review/ |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 Review |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=December 21, 2016 |last=O'Neil |first=Luke |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' gave the film a positive review.<ref>{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |author= James Verniere |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 captures the drama, horror of marathon attack |url= https://www.bostonherald.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-captures-the-drama-horror-of-marathon-attack/ |website= [[Boston Herald]] |accessdate= 2019-08-27 }}</ref>\n\nIn response Peter Berg stated that some people automatically disliked the film as they may have been in close proximity to the Boston bombings or they believed the film was made too quickly after the events had occurred.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> Katharine Q. Seelye, who was not from Boston, wrote in ''[[The New York Times]]'' that the Saunders character was \"[t]he biggest point of divergence\", as Boston-area residents disliked the [[composite character]]'s involvement in all the major events when he was not a single actual person, while people not from the Boston area \"may even appreciate [Saunders] as a narrative device\" and \"have not really questioned\" Saunders's role.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> She concluded \"that moviegoers outside New England pretty much accept the film on its own terms, as entertainment, and Bostonians do not.\"<ref name=\"Selyee\">{{cite news |date= 2017-01-13 |last= Selyee |first= Katharine Q. |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/13/movies/patriots-day-disconnect-between-bostonians-and-the-rest-of-us.html |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 Disconnect Between Bostonians and the Rest of Us |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |accessdate= 2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe [[National Board of Review Awards 2016|National Board of Review]] honored [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Peter Berg]] with their ''Spotlight Award'' for this film (and also for ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title= National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |work=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n*''[[Dark Night (2016 film)|Dark Night]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|4572514}}\n* {{AllMovie title|654626}}\n* [http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/patriots-day/ ''Patriots Day''] at ''[[History vs. Hollywood]]''\n\n{{Peter Berg}}\n{{Scott Stuber}}\n{{Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross}}\n{{Boston Athletic Association}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:CBS Films films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Thriller films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Crime films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Boston Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Berg]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Mark Wahlberg]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2013]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steve Jablonsky]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Atticus Ross]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSteal(link changed toTheft) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patriots_Day_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Marine propulsion", "text_new": "{{short description|Systems for generating thrust for ships and boats on water}}\n{{About||the operation of ship engines|Engine department (ship)|the design of ships|Naval architecture}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Two Main Engines, V12.jpg|thumb|250px|Two V12 Diesel engines in a ship's engine room]]\n'''Marine propulsion''' is the mechanism or system used to generate [[thrust]] to move a [[ship]] or [[boat]] across water. While [[paddle]]s and [[sail]]s are still used on some smaller boats, most modern ships are propelled by mechanical systems consisting of an electric motor or engine turning a [[propeller]], or less frequently, in [[pump-jet]]s, an [[impeller]]. [[Marine engineering]] is the discipline concerned with the [[engineering design process]] of marine [[propulsion system]]s.\n\nManpower, in the form of paddles, and sail were the first forms of marine propulsion. Rowed [[galley]]s, some equipped with sail, also played an important early role. The first advanced mechanical means of marine propulsion was the \n[[marine steam engine]], introduced in the early 19th century. During the 20th century it was replaced by [[Two-stroke diesel engine|two-stroke]] or [[four-stroke diesel engine]]s, outboard motors, and [[gas turbine engine]]s on faster ships.  [[nuclear marine propulsion|Marine nuclear reactors]], which appeared in the 1950s,  produce steam to propel [[warship]]s and [[icebreaker]]s; commercial application, attempted late that decade, failed to catch on. [[Electric motor]]s using electric battery storage have been used for propulsion on [[submarine]]s and [[electric boat]]s and have been proposed for energy-efficient propulsion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivt.ntnu.no/imt/electricship/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517060017/http://www.ivt.ntnu.no/imt/electricship/ |archivedate=2009-05-17 }}</ref>\n\nDevelopment in [[liquefied natural gas]] (LNG) [[internal combustion engine|fueled engines]] are gaining recognition for their low emissions and cost advantages. [[Stirling engines]], which are quieter, smoother running, propel a number of [[Applications of the Stirling engine#Marine engines|small submarines]] in order to run as quietly as possible. Its design is not used in civilian marine application due to lower total efficiency than internal combustion engines or power turbines. \n\n==Power sources==\n===Pre-mechanisation===\n[[File:Mozambique - traditional sailboat.jpg|thumb|A wind propelled fishing boat in [[Mozambique]]]]\nUntil the application of the coal-fired [[steam engine]] to ships in the early 19th century, [[oars]] or the [[wind]] were the principal means of watercraft propulsion.  Merchant ships predominantly used sail, but during periods when [[naval warfare]] depended on ships closing to [[battering ram|ram]] or to fight hand-to-hand, [[galley]] were preferred for their manoeuvrability and speed.  The [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] navies that fought in the [[Peloponnesian War]] used [[trireme]]s, as did the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] at the [[Battle of Actium]].  The development of [[naval gunnery]] from the 16th century onward vaulted broadside weight ahead of manoeuvrability; this led to the dominance of the sail-powered warship over the following three centuries.\n\nIn modern times, human propulsion is found mainly on small boats or as auxiliary propulsion on sailboats. Human propulsion includes the push pole, rowing, and pedals.\n\nPropulsion by sail generally consists of a sail hoisted on an erect mast, supported by [[standing rigging|stays]], and controlled by [[running rigging|lines]] made of [[rope]].  Sails were the dominant form of commercial propulsion until the late nineteenth century, and continued to be used well into the twentieth century on routes where wind was assured and coal was not available, such as in the South American [[nitrate trade]].  Sails are now generally used for recreation and racing, although innovative applications of [[kite]]s/[[royal (sail)|royal]]s, [[turbosail]]s, [[rotorsail]]s, [[wingsail]]s, [[windmill ship|windmills]] and [[SkySails]]'s own kite buoy-system have been used on larger modern vessels for fuel savings.\n\n===Reciprocating steam engines===\n[[File:SS Ukkopekka steam engine.jpg|thumb|{{SS|Ukkopekka}} uses a triple expansion [[steam engine]]]]\n[[File:Triple expansion engine animation.gif|thumb|How a Triple expansion steam engine works]]\n{{main|Marine steam engine}}\nThe development of [[reciprocating engine|piston-engined]] steamships was a complex process.  Early steamships were fueled by wood, later ones by coal or fuel oil.  Early ships used stern or side [[Paddle steamer|paddle wheels]], which gave way to screw [[propeller]]s.\n\nThe first commercial success accrued to [[Robert Fulton]]'s ''[[North River Steamboat]]'' (often called ''Clermont'') in US in 1807, followed in [[Europe]] by the {{convert|45|ft|m|adj=on|0}} {{PS|Comet||2}} of 1812.  Steam propulsion progressed considerably over the rest of the 19th century.  Notable developments include the steam [[surface condenser]], which eliminated the use of sea water in the ship's boilers.  This, along with improvements in boiler technology, permitted higher steam pressures, and thus the use of higher efficiency [[Steam engine#Multiple expansion engines|multiple expansion]] (compound) engines.  As the means of transmitting the engine's power, paddle wheels gave way to more efficient screw propellers.\n\nMultiple expansion steam engines became widespread in the late 19th century.  These engines exhausted steam from a high pressure cylinder to a lower pressure cylinder, giving a large increase in efficiency.<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Industrial Power in the United States, 1730\u20131930, Vol. 2: Steam  Power |last1=Hunter |first1= Louis C.|year=1985 |ref=harv| publisher =University Press of Virginia|location= Charolttesville}}</ref>\n\n===Steam turbines===\nSteam turbines were fueled by [[coal]] or, later, [[fuel oil]] or [[nuclear power]].  The marine [[steam turbine]] developed by Sir [[Charles Algernon Parsons]]<ref>[[Aurel Stodola|A Stodola]] (1927) ''Steam and Gas Trubines''. McGraw-Hill.</ref> raised the power-to-weight ratio.  He achieved publicity by demonstrating it unofficially in the {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=on|0}} ''[[Turbinia]]'' at the [[Spithead]] [[Fleet Review, Royal Navy#Queen Victoria|Naval Review]] in 1897.  This facilitated a generation of high-speed liners in the first half of the 20th century, and rendered the reciprocating steam engine obsolete; first in warships, and later in merchant vessels.\n\nIn the early 20th century, heavy fuel oil came into more general use and began to replace coal as the fuel of choice in steamships.  Its great advantages were convenience, reduced manpower by removal of the need for [[coal trimmer|trimmers]] and stokers, and reduced space needed for fuel bunkers.\n===Turbo-electric transmission ===\nTurbo-electric transmission uses electric generators to convert the mechanical energy of a turbine (steam or gas) into electric energy and electric motors to convert it back into mechanical energy to power the driveshafts.  An advantage of turbo-electric transmission is that it allows the adaptation of high-speed turbines to slow turning propellers or wheels without a heavy and complex gearbox. It has the advantage of being able to provide electricity for the ship or train's other electrical systems, such as lighting, computers, radar, and communications equipment.\n[[File:USS New Mexico BB-40 1921.jpg|thumb|The battleship {{USS|New Mexico|BB-40|6}}, {{liy|1917}}, was the World's first turbo-electric battleship.]]\n\n===Diesel===\nIn the second half of the 20th century, rising fuel costs almost led to the demise of the steam turbine.  Most new ships since around 1960 have been built with [[diesel engine]]s, both Four or two-Stroke. The last major passenger ship built with steam turbines was ''[[Pacific Sky|Fairsky]]'', launched in 1984.  Similarly, many steam ships were re-engined to improve [[fuel efficiency]].  One high-profile example was the 1968 built ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'' which had her steam turbines replaced with a [[diesel-electric]] propulsion plant in 1986.\n\nMost new-build ships with steam turbines are specialist vessels such as nuclear-powered vessels, and certain merchant vessels (notably [[Liquefied Natural Gas]] (LNG) and coal carriers) where the cargo can be used as [[bunker fuel]].\n\n====LNG carriers====\nNew [[LNG carrier]]s (a high growth area of shipping) continue to be built with steam turbines.  The natural gas is stored in a liquid state in [[cryogenics|cryogenic]] vessels aboard these ships, and a small amount of 'boil off' gas is needed to be constantly withdrawn in order to maintain the pressure and temperature inside the vessels within operating limits.  The 'boil off' gas provides the fuel for the ship's boilers, which further provide steam for the turbines, the simplest way to deal with the excessive 'boil off' gas.  However, technology to operate [[internal combustion engine]]s (modified marine two-stroke diesel engines) on this gas has improved, and such engines are starting to appear in LNG carriers. \nAlso constantly improving tank designs allow reaching greater thermal efficiency, therefore less 'boil off' naturally occurs.  Developments have also been made in the process of re-liquifying 'boil off' gas, letting it be returned to the cryogenic tanks as a liquid.  The financial returns on LNG are potentially greater than the cost of the marine-grade fuel oil burnt in conventional diesel engines, so the re-liquefaction process is starting to be used on diesel engine propelled LNG carriers.  Another factor driving the change from turbines to diesel engines for LNG carriers is the shortage of steam turbine qualified seagoing engineers.    With the lack of turbine powered ships in other shipping sectors, and the rapid rise in size of the worldwide LNG fleet, not enough have been trained to meet the demand.  It may be that the days are numbered for marine steam turbine propulsion systems, even though all but sixteen of the orders for new LNG carriers at the end of 2004 were for steam turbine propelled ships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informare.it/news/forum/2005/brs/lng-auk.asp |title=informare \u2013 Forum of Shipping and Logistics |publisher=Informare.it |accessdate=2009-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103110035/http://www.informare.it/news/forum/2005/brs/lng-auk.asp |archivedate=2009-01-03 }}{{unreliable source?|date=December 2009}}</ref>\n[[File:NSsavannah-1962.jpg|thumb|{{ship|NS|Savannah}} was the first [[nuclear marine propulsion|nuclear-powered]] cargo ship]]\n\n====Nuclear-powered steam turbines====\n{{main|Nuclear marine propulsion}}\nIn these vessels, the [[nuclear reactor]] heats water to create steam to drive the turbines.  When first developed, very low prices of diesel oil limited nuclear propulsion's commercial attraction. The advantages of its fuel-price security, greater safety and low emissions were unable to overcome the higher initial costs of a nuclear power plant. In 2019, nuclear propulsion is rare except in some [[Navy]] and specialist vessels such as [[icebreaker]]s.  In large [[aircraft carrier]]s, the space formerly used for ship's bunkerage is used instead to bunker aviation fuel.  In [[submarine]]s, the ability to run submerged at high speed and in relative quiet for long periods holds obvious advantages.  A few naval [[cruiser]]s have also employed nuclear power; as of 2006, the only ones remaining in service are the [[Russia]]n {{sclass-|Kirov|battlecruiser|4}}.  An example of a non-military ship with [[nuclear marine propulsion]] is the {{sclass-|Arktika|icebreaker|1}} with {{convert|75000|shp|-1|lk=on}}. In an ice-breaker, an advantage is fuel security and safety in demanding arctic conditions.  The commercial experiment of the {{ship|NS|Savannah}} ended before the dramatic fuel price increases of the 1970s. The Savannah also suffered from an inefficient design, being partly for passengers and partly for cargo.\n\nIn recent times, there is some renewed interest in commercial nuclear shipping. Fuel oil prices are now much higher. Nuclear-powered cargo ships could lower costs associated with carbon dioxide emissions and travel at higher cruise speeds than conventional diesel powered vessels.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_Full_steam_ahead_for_nuclear_shipping_1811101.html |title=Full steam ahead for nuclear shipping |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=2010-11-18 |accessdate=2011-02-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223175319/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_Full_steam_ahead_for_nuclear_shipping_1811101.html |archivedate=2010-12-23 }}</ref>\n\n===Reciprocating diesel engines===\n[[Image:MainEngine1.JPG|thumb|A modern [[diesel engine]] aboard a cargo ship]]\n[[File:Diesel engine Uniflow.PNG|thumb|Intake and exhaust flow in a 2-stroke heavy-duty[[diesel engine]] ]]\n\nMost modern ships use a reciprocating [[diesel engine]] as their prime mover, due to their operating simplicity, robustness and fuel economy compared to most other prime mover mechanisms.  The rotating [[crankshaft]] can be directly coupled to the propeller with slow speed engines, via a reduction gearbox for medium and high speed engines, or via an alternator and electric motor in diesel-electric vessels. The rotation of the crankshaft is connected to the camshaft or a hydraulic pump on an [[Intelligent Diesel Engine|intelligent diesel]].\n\nThe reciprocating marine diesel engine first came into use in 1903 when the [[diesel-electric transmission|diesel electric]] rivertanker [[Vandal (tanker)|''Vandal'']] was put into service by [[Branobel]].  Diesel engines soon offered greater efficiency than the steam turbine, but for many years had an inferior power-to-space ratio.  The advent of turbocharging however hastened their adoption, by permitting greater power densities.\n\nDiesel engines today are broadly classified according to\n*Their operating cycle: [[two-stroke engine]] or [[four-stroke engine]]\n*Their construction: [[crosshead]], [[trunk engine|trunk]], or [[opposed piston engine|opposed piston]]\n*Their speed\n**Slow speed: any engine with a maximum operating speed up to 300&nbsp;[[revolutions per minute]] (rpm), although most large two-stroke slow speed diesel engines operate below 120&nbsp;rpm.  Some very long stroke engines have a maximum speed of around 80&nbsp;rpm.  The largest, most powerful engines in the world are slow speed, two stroke, crosshead diesels.\n**Medium speed: any engine with a maximum operating speed in the range 300\u20131000&nbsp;rpm.  Many modern four-stroke medium speed diesel engines have a maximum operating speed of around 500&nbsp;rpm.\n**High speed: any engine with a maximum operating speed above 1000&nbsp;rpm.\n[[File:Marine-propulsion-system.jpg|thumb|4-Stroke Marine Diesel Engine System]]\nMost modern larger merchant ships use either slow speed, two stroke, crosshead engines, or medium speed, four stroke, trunk engines.  Some smaller vessels may use high speed diesel engines.\n\nThe size of the different types of engines is an important factor in selecting what will be installed in a new ship.  Slow speed two-stroke engines are much taller, but the footprint required is smaller than that needed for equivalently rated four-stroke medium speed diesel engines.  As space above the waterline is at a premium in passenger ships and ferries (especially ones with a car deck), these ships tend to use multiple medium speed engines resulting in a longer, lower engine room than that needed for two-stroke diesel engines.  Multiple engine installations also give redundancy in the event of mechanical failure of one or more engines, and the potential for greater efficiency over a wider range of operating conditions.\n\nAs modern ships' propellers are at their most efficient at the operating speed of most slow speed diesel engines, ships with these engines do not generally need gearboxes.  Usually such propulsion systems consist of either one or two propeller shafts each with its own direct drive engine.  Ships propelled by medium or high speed diesel engines may have one or two (sometimes more) propellers, commonly with one or more engines driving each propeller shaft through a gearbox.  Where more than one engine is geared to a single shaft, each engine will most likely drive through a clutch, allowing engines not being used to be disconnected from the gearbox while others keep running.  This arrangement lets maintenance be carried out while under way, even far from port.\n\n===LNG Engines===\nShipping companies are required to comply with the [[International Maritime Organization]] (IMO) and the [[MARPOL 73/78|International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from Ships]] emissions rules. Dual fuel engines are fueled by either marine grade diesel, heavy fuel oil, or liquefied natural gas (LNG). A [[Marine LNG Engine]] has multiple fuel options, allowing vessels to transit without relying on one type of fuel.  Studies show that LNG is the most efficient of fuels, although limited access to LNG fueling stations limits the production of such engines.  Vessels providing services in the LNG industry have been retrofitted with dual-fuel engines, and have been proved to be extremely effective.  Benefits of dual-fuel engines include fuel and operational flexibility, high efficiency, low emissions, and operational cost advantages.\nLiquefied natural gas engines offer the marine transportation industry with an environmentally friendly alternative to provide power to vessels.  In 2010, STX Finland and Viking Line signed an agreement to begin construction on what would be the largest environmentally friendly cruise ferry.  Construction of NB 1376 will be completed in 2013.  According to Viking Line, vessel NB 1376 will primarily be fueled by liquefied natural gas. Vessel NB 1376 nitrogen oxide emissions will be almost zero, and sulphur oxide emissions will be at least 80% below the International Maritime Organization\u2019s (IMO) standards.\nCompany profits from tax cuts and operational cost advantages has led to the gradual growth of LNG fuel use in engines.\n<ref>LNG World News. (2010) STX Finland and Viking Line sign agreement for cruise ferry. Retrieved December 15, 2011 from {{cite web |url=http://www.lngworldnews.com/stx-finland-and-viking-line-sign-agreement-for-cruise-ferry/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114141600/http://www.lngworldnews.com/stx-finland-and-viking-line-sign-agreement-for-cruise-ferry/ |archivedate=2012-01-14 }}\nW\u00e4rtsil\u00e4. (2011) W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 dual-fuel power plants. Power plants. Retrieved December 15, 2011, from {{cite web |url=http://wartsila.com/en/power-plants/smart-power-generation/dual-fuel-power-plants |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219220535/http://www.wartsila.com/en/power-plants/smart-power-generation/dual-fuel-power-plants |archivedate=2011-12-19 }}\nViking Line. (2011) LNG is our choice. Environment. Retrieved December 15, 2011, from www.nb1376.com\n</ref>\n\n===Gas turbines===\n{{Combined-marine-propulsion}}\nMany warships built since the 1960s have used [[gas turbine]]s for propulsion, as have a few passenger ships, like the [[jetfoil]].  Gas turbines are commonly used in combination with other types of engine.  Most recently, {{RMS|Queen Mary 2}} has had gas turbines installed in addition to [[diesel engines]].  Because of their poor thermal efficiency at low power (cruising) output, it is common for ships using them to have diesel engines for cruising, with gas turbines reserved for when higher speeds are needed. However, in the case of passenger ships the main reason for installing gas turbines has been to allow a reduction of emissions in sensitive environmental areas or while in port.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCP/is_1_26/ai_n6100061|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060224153308/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCP/is_1_26/ai_n6100061|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-02-24|title=Return of the turbine \u2013 Cruise Travel|publisher=FindArticles.com|date=2004-07-01|accessdate=2009-04-21}}</ref>  Some warships, and a few modern cruise ships have also used steam turbines to improve the efficiency of their gas turbines in a [[combined cycle]], where [[waste heat]] from a gas turbine exhaust is utilized to boil water and create steam for driving a steam turbine.  In such combined cycles, thermal efficiency can be the same or slightly greater than that of diesel engines alone; however, the grade of fuel needed for these gas turbines is far more costly than that needed for the diesel engines, so the running costs are still higher.\n\n===Stirling engines===\nSince the late 1980s, Swedish shipbuilder [[Kockums]] has built a number of successful Stirling engine powered submarines.<ref>{{cite web | author = | title = The Kockums Stirling AIP system&nbsp;\u2013 proven in operational service | publisher = Kockums | url = http://www.sesusa.org/submarine.pdf | accessdate=2011-06-07}}</ref><ref name=\"Kockums\">Kockums (a)</ref> The submarines store compressed oxygen to allow more efficient and cleaner external fuel combustion when submerged, providing heat for the Stirling engine's operation. The engines are currently used on submarines of the {{sclass-|Gotland|submarine|5}} and {{sclass-|S\u00f6dermanland|submarine|5}} classes. and the Japanese {{sclass-|S\u014dry\u016b|submarine|0}} submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/products/janes/defence-security-report.aspx?ID=1065926751&pu=1&rd=janes_com|title=First Improved Oyashio-class boat takes to the water|date=June 12, 2007|publisher=IHS|accessdate=June 3, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110607184930/http://www.janes.com/products/janes/defence-security-report.aspx?ID=1065926751&pu=1&rd=janes_com| archivedate= 7 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> These are the first submarines to feature Stirling [[air-independent propulsion]] (AIP), which extends the underwater endurance from a few days to several weeks.<ref name=\"Kockums\" />\n\nThe heat sink of a Stirling engine is typically the ambient air temperature. In the case of medium to high power Stirling engines, a [[radiator]] is generally required to transfer the heat from the engine to the ambient air. Stirling marine engines have the advantage of using the ambient temperature water. Placing the cooling radiator section in seawater rather than ambient air allows for the radiator to be smaller. The engine's cooling water may be used directly or indirectly for heating and cooling purposes of the ship.  The Stirling engine has potential for surface-ship propulsion, as the engine's larger physical size is less of a concern.\n\n===Electric===\n{{seealso|Electric boat}}\nBattery generated electric propulsion first appeared in the latter part of the 19th century, powering small lake boats.  These relied entirely on [[lead-acid battery|lead-acid batteries]] for electric current to power their propellers.  [[Electric Launch Company|Elco]] (the Electric Launch Company) evolved into the industry leader, later expanding into other forms of vessel, including the iconic World War II [[PT boat]].\n\nIn the early part of the 20th century electric propulsion was adapted to use in [[submarine]]s. As underwater propulsion driven exclusively by heavy batteries was both slow and of limited range and timespan, rechargeable battery banks were developed.  Submarines were primarily powered by combined [[diesel-electric]] systems on the surface, which were much faster and allowed for dramatically expanded range, charging their battery systems as necessary for still limited subsurface action and duration. The [[Plunger (experimental submarine)|Holland V]] submarine led to the adoption of this system by the [[U.S. Navy]], followed by the [[British Royal Navy]].\n\nTo expand the range and duration of the submarine during World War II the German [[Kriegsmarine]] developed a [[Submarine snorkel|snorkel]] system, which allowed the diesel-electric system to be utilized while the submarine was all but completely submerged. Finally, in 1952, the [[USS Nautilus (SSN-571)|USS ''Nautilus'']] was launched, the world's first nuclear powered submarine, which eliminated the restrictions of both diesel fuel and limited duration battery propulsion.\n\n[[Electric boat#List of battery-electric ships|Several short-range ships are built as (or converted to) pure electric vessels]]. This includes some powered by batteries which are recharged from shore, and some [[shore-power]]ed by [[Electric boat#Wired electric boats|electrical cables]], [[Straussee Ferry|either]] [[Canby Ferry|overhead]] or [[Kastellet ferry|submerged]] (no batteries).\n\nOn November 12, 2017 [[Guangzhou Shipyard International]] (GSI) launched what may be the world's first all-electric, battery-powered inland coal carrier. The 2,000 dwt vessel will carry bulk cargo for up to 40 nautical miles per charge. The ship carries [[lithium ion batteries]] rated at 2,400 kilowatt-hours, about the same amount as 30 [[Tesla Model S]] electric sedans.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://maritime-executive.com/article/chinese-yard-launches-battery-powered-coal-carrier |title=Chinese Yard Launches Battery-Powered Coal Carrier |url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171115020231/https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/chinese-yard-launches-battery-powered-coal-carrier |archivedate=2017-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/china-launches-world-s-first-fully-electric-cargo-ship/story-ceg5ZbMb67yOLpYFZNdg4I.html |title=China launches world\u2019s first fully electric cargo ship|date=14 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171115143658/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/china-launches-world-s-first-fully-electric-cargo-ship/story-ceg5ZbMb67yOLpYFZNdg4I.html |archivedate=15 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Propulsion types==\nNumerous types of propulsion have been developed over time. These include:\n\n===Propeller===\n{{Main|Propeller}}\nMarine propellers are also known as \"screws\". There are many variations of marine screw systems, including twin, contra-rotating, controllable-pitch, and nozzle-style screws.  While smaller vessels tend to have a single screw, even very large ships such as tankers, container ships and bulk carriers may have single screws for reasons of fuel efficiency.  Other vessels may have twin, triple or quadruple screws.  Power is transmitted from the engine to the screw by way of a propeller shaft, which may be connected to a gearbox.\n\n===Paddle wheel===\n[[File:Paddle wheel small.jpg|thumb|Left: original paddle wheel from a paddle steamer.<br>Right: detail of a paddle steamer.]]\n{{See also|Paddle steamer|Pedalo}}\nThe paddle wheel is a large wheel, generally built of a [[steel frame]]work, upon the outer edge of which are fitted numerous paddle blades (called ''floats'' or ''buckets'').  The bottom quarter or so of the wheel travels underwater.  Rotation of the paddle wheel produces [[thrust]], forward or backward as required.  More advanced paddle wheel designs have featured ''feathering'' methods that keep each paddle blade oriented closer to vertical while it is in the water; this increases efficiency.  The upper part of a paddle wheel is normally enclosed in a paddlebox to minimise splashing.\n\nPaddle wheels have been superseded by screws, which are a much more efficient form of propulsion.  Nevertheless, paddle wheels have two advantages over screws, making them suitable for vessels in  shallow rivers and constrained waters: first, they are less likely to be clogged by obstacles and debris; and secondly, when contra-rotating, they allow the vessel to spin around its own vertical axis.  Some vessels had a single screw in addition to two paddle wheels, to gain the advantages of both types of propulsion.\n\n===Pump jet===\n{{main|pump-jet}}\nA '''pump-jet''', '''hydrojet''', '''water jet''', or '''jet drive''' uses a [[ducted propeller]] ([[axial-flow pump]]), [[centrifugal pump]], or mixed flow pump to create a jet of water for propulsion.\n\nThese incorporate an intake for source water and a nozzle to direct its flow out, generating momentum, and in most cases, employing thrust vectoring to steer the craft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hamiltonmarine.co.nz/includes/files_cms/file/JetTorque%2008.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-10-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120110527/http://hamiltonmarine.co.nz/includes/files_cms/file/JetTorque%2008.pdf |archivedate=2018-01-20 }}</ref>\n\nPump-jets are found on [[personal watercraft]], shallow-draft river boats, and torpedoes.\n\n===Sail===\n{{main|Forces on sails}}\nThe purpose of [[sail]]s is to use [[wind]] [[energy]] to propel the [[sailboat|vessel]], [[ice boat|sled]], [[sailboard|board]], [[land sailing|vehicle]] or  [[windmill sail|rotor]].\n\n===Voith-Schneider cyclo-rotor===\n[[Image:VSPreal.jpg|right|thumb|100px|Voith Schneider Propeller]]\nA [[Voith Schneider Propeller]] (VSP) is a practical [[cyclorotor]] that provides instant thrust in any direction. There is no need to turn a propulsor. Most ships with VSPs do not need or have a rudder. VSPs are often used in tugboats, drilling vessels, and other watercraft that require unusually good maneuverability. First deployed in the 1930s, Voith-Schneider drives are both reliable and available in large sizes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://voith.com/corp-en/drives-transmissions/voith-schneider-propeller-vsp.html |publisher=Voith Global GMBH |accessdate=10 November 2019 |title=Voith Schneider Propeller VSP}}</ref>\n\n===Caterpillar===\n[[File:Popular Science Dec 1918 p68 - History of boat propulsion, Water caterpillar.jpg|thumb|right|The water caterpillar boat propulsion system ([[Popular Science]] Monthly, December 1918)]]\nAn early uncommon means of boat propulsion was the water caterpillar.  This moved a series of paddles on chains along the bottom of the boat to propel it over the water and preceded the development of [[tracked vehicle]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Caterpillar Is Now Being Applied to Ships|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EikDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA68|date=December 1918|publisher=Popular Science|page=68}}</ref> The first water caterpillar was developed by [[:de:Joseph-Philibert Desblanc|Joseph-Philibert Desblanc]] in 1782 and propelled by a steam engine. In the United States the first water caterpillar was patented in 1839 by William Leavenworth of New York.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\n==Buoyancy==\n[[Underwater gliders]] convert buoyancy to thrust, using wings, or more recently hull shape (SeaExplorer Glider). Buoyancy is made alternatively negative and positive, generating tooth-saw profiles.\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n*{{annotated link|Air-independent propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Astern propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Combined nuclear and steam propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Diesel generator}}\n*{{annotated link|Experiment (horse-powered boat)|''Experiment'' (horse-powered boat)}}\n*{{annotated link|Integrated electric propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Internal drive propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Non-road engine}}\n*{{annotated link|Nuclear marine propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Wind-assisted propulsion}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marine Propulsion}}\n[[Category:Marine propulsion]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Systems for generating thrust for ships and boats on water}}\n{{About||the operation of ship engines|Engine department (ship)|the design of ships|Naval architecture}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Two Main Engines, V12.jpg|thumb|250px|Two V12 Diesel engines in a ship's engine room]]\n'''Marine propulsion''' is the mechanism or system used to generate [[thrust]] to move a [[ship]] or [[boat]] across water. While [[paddle]]s and [[sail]]s are still used on some smaller boats, most modern ships are propelled by mechanical systems consisting of an electric motor or engine turning a [[propeller]], or less frequently, in [[pump-jet]]s, an [[impeller]]. [[Marine engineering]] is the discipline concerned with the [[engineering design process]] of marine [[propulsion system]]s.\n\nManpower, in the form of paddles, and sail were the first forms of marine propulsion. Rowed [[galley]]s, some equipped with sail, also played an important early role. The first advanced mechanical means of marine propulsion was the \n[[marine steam engine]], introduced in the early 19th century. During the 20th century it was replaced by [[Two-stroke diesel engine|two-stroke]] or [[four-stroke diesel engine]]s, outboard motors, and [[gas turbine engine]]s on faster ships.  [[nuclear marine propulsion|Marine nuclear reactors]], which appeared in the 1950s,  produce steam to propel [[warship]]s and [[icebreaker]]s; commercial application, attempted late that decade, failed to catch on. [[Electric motor]]s using electric battery storage have been used for propulsion on [[submarine]]s and [[electric boat]]s and have been proposed for energy-efficient propulsion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ivt.ntnu.no/imt/electricship/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090517060017/http://www.ivt.ntnu.no/imt/electricship/ |archivedate=2009-05-17 }}</ref>\n\nDevelopment in [[liquefied natural gas]] (LNG) [[internal combustion engine|fueled engines]] are gaining recognition for their low emissions and cost advantages. [[Stirling engines]], which are quieter, smoother running, propel a number of [[Applications of the Stirling engine#Marine engines|small submarines]] in order to run as quietly as possible. Its design is not used in civilian marine application due to lower total efficiency than internal combustion engines or power turbines. \n\n==Power sources==\n===Pre-mechanisation===\n[[File:Mozambique - traditional sailboat.jpg|thumb|A wind propelled fishing boat in [[Mozambique]]]]\nUntil the application of the coal-fired [[steam engine]] to ships in the early 19th century, [[oars]] or the [[wind]] were the principal means of watercraft propulsion.  Merchant ships predominantly used sail, but during periods when [[naval warfare]] depended on ships closing to [[battering ram|ram]] or to fight hand-to-hand, [[galley]] were preferred for their manoeuvrability and speed.  The [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] navies that fought in the [[Peloponnesian War]] used [[trireme]]s, as did the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] at the [[Battle of Actium]].  The development of [[naval gunnery]] from the 16th century onward vaulted broadside weight ahead of manoeuvrability; this led to the dominance of the sail-powered warship over the following three centuries.\n\nIn modern times, human propulsion is found mainly on small boats or as auxiliary propulsion on sailboats. Human propulsion includes the push pole, rowing, and pedals.\n\nPropulsion by sail generally consists of a sail hoisted on an erect mast, supported by [[standing rigging|stays]], and controlled by [[running rigging|lines]] made of [[rope]].  Sails were the dominant form of commercial propulsion until the late nineteenth century, and continued to be used well into the twentieth century on routes where wind was assured and coal was not available, such as in the South American [[nitrate trade]].  Sails are now generally used for recreation and racing, although innovative applications of [[kite]]s/[[royal (sail)|royal]]s, [[turbosail]]s, [[rotorsail]]s, [[wingsail]]s, [[windmill ship|windmills]] and [[SkySails]]'s own kite buoy-system have been used on larger modern vessels for fuel savings.\n\n===Reciprocating steam engines===\n[[File:SS Ukkopekka steam engine.jpg|thumb|{{SS|Ukkopekka}} uses a triple expansion [[steam engine]]]]\n[[File:Triple expansion engine animation.gif|thumb|How a Triple expansion steam engine works]]\n{{main|Marine steam engine}}\nThe development of [[reciprocating engine|piston-engined]] steamships was a complex process.  Early steamships were fueled by wood, later ones by coal or fuel oil.  Early ships used stern or side [[Paddle steamer|paddle wheels]], which gave way to screw [[propeller]]s.\n\nThe first commercial success accrued to [[Robert Fulton]]'s ''[[North River Steamboat]]'' (often called ''Clermont'') in US in 1807, followed in [[Europe]] by the {{convert|45|ft|m|adj=on|0}} {{PS|Comet||2}} of 1812.  Steam propulsion progressed considerably over the rest of the 19th century.  Notable developments include the steam [[surface condenser]], which eliminated the use of sea water in the ship's boilers.  This, along with improvements in boiler technology, permitted higher steam pressures, and thus the use of higher efficiency [[Steam engine#Multiple expansion engines|multiple expansion]] (compound) engines.  As the means of transmitting the engine's power, paddle wheels gave way to more efficient screw propellers.\n\nMultiple expansion steam engines became widespread in the late 19th century.  These engines exhausted steam from a high pressure cylinder to a lower pressure cylinder, giving a large increase in efficiency.<ref>{{cite book |title=A History of Industrial Power in the United States, 1730\u20131930, Vol. 2: Steam  Power |last1=Hunter |first1= Louis C.|year=1985 |ref=harv| publisher =University Press of Virginia|location= Charolttesville}}</ref>\n\n===Steam turbines===\nSteam turbines were fueled by [[coal]] or, later, [[fuel oil]] or [[nuclear power]].  The marine [[steam turbine]] developed by Sir [[Charles Algernon Parsons]]<ref>[[Aurel Stodola|A Stodola]] (1927) ''Steam and Gas Trubines''. McGraw-Hill.</ref> raised the power-to-weight ratio.  He achieved publicity by demonstrating it unofficially in the {{convert|100|ft|m|adj=on|0}} ''[[Turbinia]]'' at the [[Spithead]] [[Fleet Review, Royal Navy#Queen Victoria|Naval Review]] in 1897.  This facilitated a generation of high-speed liners in the first half of the 20th century, and rendered the reciprocating steam engine obsolete; first in warships, and later in merchant vessels.\n\nIn the early 20th century, heavy fuel oil came into more general use and began to replace coal as the fuel of choice in steamships.  Its great advantages were convenience, reduced manpower by removal of the need for [[coal trimmer|trimmers]] and stokers, and reduced space needed for fuel bunkers.\n===Turbo-electric transmission ===\nTurbo-electric transmission uses electric generators to convert the mechanical energy of a turbine (steam or gas) into electric energy and electric motors to convert it back into mechanical energy to power the driveshafts.  An advantage of turbo-electric transmission is that it allows the adaptation of high-speed turbines to slow turning propellers or wheels without a heavy and complex gearbox. It has the advantage of being able to provide electricity for the ship or train's other electrical systems, such as lighting, computers, radar, and communications equipment.\n[[File:USS New Mexico BB-40 1921.jpg|thumb|The battleship {{USS|New Mexico|BB-40|6}}, {{liy|1917}}, was the World's first turbo-electric battleship.]]\n\n===Diesel===\nIn the second half of the 20th century, rising fuel costs almost led to the demise of the steam turbine.  Most new ships since around 1960 have been built with [[diesel engine]]s, both Four or two-Stroke. The last major passenger ship built with steam turbines was ''[[Pacific Sky|Fairsky]]'', launched in 1984.  Similarly, many steam ships were re-engined to improve [[fuel efficiency]].  One high-profile example was the 1968 built ''[[Queen Elizabeth 2]]'' which had her steam turbines replaced with a [[diesel-electric]] propulsion plant in 1986.\n\nMost new-build ships with steam turbines are specialist vessels such as nuclear-powered vessels, and certain merchant vessels (notably [[Liquefied Natural Gas]] (LNG) and coal carriers) where the cargo can be used as [[bunker fuel]].\n\n====LNG carriers====\nNew [[LNG carrier]]s (a high growth area of shipping) continue to be built with steam turbines.  The natural gas is stored in a liquid state in [[cryogenics|cryogenic]] vessels aboard these ships, and a small amount of 'boil off' gas is needed to be constantly withdrawn in order to maintain the pressure and temperature inside the vessels within operating limits.  The 'boil off' gas provides the fuel for the ship's boilers, which further provide steam for the turbines, the simplest way to deal with the excessive 'boil off' gas.  However, technology to operate [[internal combustion engine]]s (modified marine two-stroke diesel engines) on this gas has improved, and such engines are starting to appear in LNG carriers. \nAlso constantly improving tank designs allow reaching greater thermal efficiency, therefore less 'boil off' naturally occurs.  Developments have also been made in the process of re-liquifying 'boil off' gas, letting it be returned to the cryogenic tanks as a liquid.  The financial returns on LNG are potentially greater than the cost of the marine-grade fuel oil burnt in conventional diesel engines, so the re-liquefaction process is starting to be used on diesel engine propelled LNG carriers.  Another factor driving the change from turbines to diesel engines for LNG carriers is the shortage of steam turbine qualified seagoing engineers.    With the lack of turbine powered ships in other shipping sectors, and the rapid rise in size of the worldwide LNG fleet, not enough have been trained to meet the demand.  It may be that the days are numbered for marine steam turbine propulsion systems, even though all but sixteen of the orders for new LNG carriers at the end of 2004 were for steam turbine propelled ships.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informare.it/news/forum/2005/brs/lng-auk.asp |title=informare \u2013 Forum of Shipping and Logistics |publisher=Informare.it |accessdate=2009-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090103110035/http://www.informare.it/news/forum/2005/brs/lng-auk.asp |archivedate=2009-01-03 }}{{unreliable source?|date=December 2009}}</ref>\n[[File:NSsavannah-1962.jpg|thumb|{{ship|NS|Savannah}} was the first [[nuclear marine propulsion|nuclear-powered]] cargo ship]]\n\n====Nuclear-powered steam turbines====\n{{main|Nuclear marine propulsion}}\nIn these vessels, the [[nuclear reactor]] heats water to create steam to drive the turbines.  When first developed, very low prices of diesel oil limited nuclear propulsion's commercial attraction. The advantages of its fuel-price security, greater safety and low emissions were unable to overcome the higher initial costs of a nuclear power plant. In 2019, nuclear propulsion is rare except in some [[Navy]] and specialist vessels such as [[icebreaker]]s.  In large [[aircraft carrier]]s, the space formerly used for ship's bunkerage is used instead to bunker aviation fuel.  In [[submarine]]s, the ability to run submerged at high speed and in relative quiet for long periods holds obvious advantages.  A few naval [[cruiser]]s have also employed nuclear power; as of 2006, the only ones remaining in service are the [[Russia]]n {{sclass-|Kirov|battlecruiser|4}}.  An example of a non-military ship with [[nuclear marine propulsion]] is the {{sclass-|Arktika|icebreaker|1}} with {{convert|75000|shp|-1|lk=on}}. In an ice-breaker, an advantage is fuel security and safety in demanding arctic conditions.  The commercial experiment of the {{ship|NS|Savannah}} ended before the dramatic fuel price increases of the 1970s. The Savannah also suffered from an inefficient design, being partly for passengers and partly for cargo.\n\nIn recent times, there is some renewed interest in commercial nuclear shipping. Fuel oil prices are now much higher. Nuclear-powered cargo ships could lower costs associated with carbon dioxide emissions and travel at higher cruise speeds than conventional diesel powered vessels.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_Full_steam_ahead_for_nuclear_shipping_1811101.html |title=Full steam ahead for nuclear shipping |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=2010-11-18 |accessdate=2011-02-22 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223175319/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_Full_steam_ahead_for_nuclear_shipping_1811101.html |archivedate=2010-12-23 }}</ref>\n\n===Reciprocating diesel engines===\n[[Image:MainEngine1.JPG|thumb|A modern [[diesel engine]] aboard a cargo ship]]\n[[File:Diesel engine Uniflow.PNG|thumb|Intake and exhaust flow in a 2-stroke heavy-duty[[diesel engine]] ]]\n\nMost modern ships use a reciprocating [[diesel engine]] as their prime mover, due to their operating simplicity, robustness and fuel economy compared to most other prime mover mechanisms.  The rotating [[crankshaft]] can be directly coupled to the propeller with slow speed engines, via a reduction gearbox for medium and high speed engines, or via an alternator and electric motor in diesel-electric vessels. The rotation of the crankshaft is connected to the camshaft or a hydraulic pump on an [[Intelligent Diesel Engine|intelligent diesel]].\n\nThe reciprocating marine diesel engine first came into use in 1903 when the [[diesel-electric transmission|diesel electric]] rivertanker [[Vandal (tanker)|''Vandal'']] was put into service by [[Branobel]].  Diesel engines soon offered greater efficiency than the steam turbine, but for many years had an inferior power-to-space ratio.  The advent of turbocharging however hastened their adoption, by permitting greater power densities.\n\nDiesel engines today are broadly classified according to\n*Their operating cycle: [[two-stroke engine]] or [[four-stroke engine]]\n*Their construction: [[crosshead]], [[trunk engine|trunk]], or [[opposed piston engine|opposed piston]]\n*Their speed\n**Slow speed: any engine with a maximum operating speed up to 300&nbsp;[[revolutions per minute]] (rpm), although most large two-stroke slow speed diesel engines operate below 120&nbsp;rpm.  Some very long stroke engines have a maximum speed of around 80&nbsp;rpm.  The largest, most powerful engines in the world are slow speed, two stroke, crosshead diesels.\n**Medium speed: any engine with a maximum operating speed in the range 300\u20131000&nbsp;rpm.  Many modern four-stroke medium speed diesel engines have a maximum operating speed of around 500&nbsp;rpm.\n**High speed: any engine with a maximum operating speed above 1000&nbsp;rpm.\n[[File:Marine-propulsion-system.jpg|thumb|4-Stroke Marine Diesel Engine System]]\nMost modern larger merchant ships use either slow speed, two stroke, crosshead engines, or medium speed, four stroke, trunk engines.  Some smaller vessels may use high speed diesel engines.\n\nThe size of the different types of engines is an important factor in selecting what will be installed in a new ship.  Slow speed two-stroke engines are much taller, but the footprint required is smaller than that needed for equivalently rated four-stroke medium speed diesel engines.  As space above the waterline is at a premium in passenger ships and ferries (especially ones with a car deck), these ships tend to use multiple medium speed engines resulting in a longer, lower engine room than that needed for two-stroke diesel engines.  Multiple engine installations also give redundancy in the event of mechanical failure of one or more engines, and the potential for greater efficiency over a wider range of operating conditions.\n\nAs modern ships' propellers are at their most efficient at the operating speed of most slow speed diesel engines, ships with these engines do not generally need gearboxes.  Usually such propulsion systems consist of either one or two propeller shafts each with its own direct drive engine.  Ships propelled by medium or high speed diesel engines may have one or two (sometimes more) propellers, commonly with one or more engines driving each propeller shaft through a gearbox.  Where more than one engine is geared to a single shaft, each engine will most likely drive through a clutch, allowing engines not being used to be disconnected from the gearbox while others keep running.  This arrangement lets maintenance be carried out while under way, even far from port.\n\n===LNG Engines===\nShipping companies are required to comply with the [[International Maritime Organization]] (IMO) and the [[MARPOL 73/78|International Convention for the Prevention of Pollution from Ships]] emissions rules. Dual fuel engines are fueled by either marine grade diesel, heavy fuel oil, or liquefied natural gas (LNG). A [[Marine LNG Engine]] has multiple fuel options, allowing vessels to transit without relying on one type of fuel.  Studies show that LNG is the most efficient of fuels, although limited access to LNG fueling stations limits the production of such engines.  Vessels providing services in the LNG industry have been retrofitted with dual-fuel engines, and have been proved to be extremely effective.  Benefits of dual-fuel engines include fuel and operational flexibility, high efficiency, low emissions, and operational cost advantages.\nLiquefied natural gas engines offer the marine transportation industry with an environmentally friendly alternative to provide power to vessels.  In 2010, STX Finland and Viking Line signed an agreement to begin construction on what would be the largest environmentally friendly cruise ferry.  Construction of NB 1376 will be completed in 2013.  According to Viking Line, vessel NB 1376 will primarily be fueled by liquefied natural gas. Vessel NB 1376 nitrogen oxide emissions will be almost zero, and sulphur oxide emissions will be at least 80% below the International Maritime Organization\u2019s (IMO) standards.\nCompany profits from tax cuts and operational cost advantages has led to the gradual growth of LNG fuel use in engines.\n<ref>LNG World News. (2010) STX Finland and Viking Line sign agreement for cruise ferry. Retrieved December 15, 2011 from {{cite web |url=http://www.lngworldnews.com/stx-finland-and-viking-line-sign-agreement-for-cruise-ferry/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120114141600/http://www.lngworldnews.com/stx-finland-and-viking-line-sign-agreement-for-cruise-ferry/ |archivedate=2012-01-14 }}\nW\u00e4rtsil\u00e4. (2011) W\u00e4rtsil\u00e4 dual-fuel power plants. Power plants. Retrieved December 15, 2011, from {{cite web |url=http://wartsila.com/en/power-plants/smart-power-generation/dual-fuel-power-plants |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219220535/http://www.wartsila.com/en/power-plants/smart-power-generation/dual-fuel-power-plants |archivedate=2011-12-19 }}\nViking Line. (2011) LNG is our choice. Environment. Retrieved December 15, 2011, from www.nb1376.com\n</ref>\n\n===Gas turbines===\n{{Combined-marine-propulsion}}\nMany warships built since the 1960s have used [[gas turbine]]s for propulsion, as have a few passenger ships, like the [[jetfoil]].  Gas turbines are commonly used in combination with other types of engine.  Most recently, {{RMS|Queen Mary 2}} has had gas turbines installed in addition to [[diesel engines]].  Because of their poor thermal efficiency at low power (cruising) output, it is common for ships using them to have diesel engines for cruising, with gas turbines reserved for when higher speeds are needed. However, in the case of passenger ships the main reason for installing gas turbines has been to allow a reduction of emissions in sensitive environmental areas or while in port.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCP/is_1_26/ai_n6100061|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060224153308/http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCP/is_1_26/ai_n6100061|url-status=dead|archive-date=2006-02-24|title=Return of the turbine \u2013 Cruise Travel|publisher=FindArticles.com|date=2004-07-01|accessdate=2009-04-21}}</ref>  Some warships, and a few modern cruise ships have also used steam turbines to improve the efficiency of their gas turbines in a [[combined cycle]], where [[waste heat]] from a gas turbine exhaust is utilized to boil water and create steam for driving a steam turbine.  In such combined cycles, thermal efficiency can be the same or slightly greater than that of diesel engines alone; however, the grade of fuel needed for these gas turbines is far more costly than that needed for the diesel engines, so the running costs are still higher.\n\n===Stirling engines===\nSince the late 1980s, Swedish shipbuilder [[Kockums]] has built a number of successful Stirling engine powered submarines.<ref>{{cite web | author = | title = The Kockums Stirling AIP system&nbsp;\u2013 proven in operational service | publisher = Kockums | url = http://www.sesusa.org/submarine.pdf | accessdate=2011-06-07}}</ref><ref name=\"Kockums\">Kockums (a)</ref> The submarines store compressed oxygen to allow more efficient and cleaner external fuel combustion when submerged, providing heat for the Stirling engine's operation. The engines are currently used on submarines of the {{sclass-|Gotland|submarine|5}} and {{sclass-|S\u00f6dermanland|submarine|5}} classes. and the Japanese {{sclass-|S\u014dry\u016b|submarine|0}} submarine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/products/janes/defence-security-report.aspx?ID=1065926751&pu=1&rd=janes_com|title=First Improved Oyashio-class boat takes to the water|date=June 12, 2007|publisher=IHS|accessdate=June 3, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110607184930/http://www.janes.com/products/janes/defence-security-report.aspx?ID=1065926751&pu=1&rd=janes_com| archivedate= 7 June 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> These are the first submarines to feature Stirling [[air-independent propulsion]] (AIP), which extends the underwater endurance from a few days to several weeks.<ref name=\"Kockums\" />\n\nThe heat sink of a Stirling engine is typically the ambient air temperature. In the case of medium to high power Stirling engines, a [[radiator]] is generally required to transfer the heat from the engine to the ambient air. Stirling marine engines have the advantage of using the ambient temperature water. Placing the cooling radiator section in seawater rather than ambient air allows for the radiator to be smaller. The engine's cooling water may be used directly or indirectly for heating and cooling purposes of the ship.  The Stirling engine has potential for surface-ship propulsion, as the engine's larger physical size is less of a concern.\n\n===Electric===\n{{seealso|Electric boat}}\nBattery generated electric propulsion first appeared in the latter part of the 19th century, powering small lake boats.  These relied entirely on [[lead-acid battery|lead-acid batteries]] for electric current to power their propellers.  [[Electric Launch Company|Elco]] (the Electric Launch Company) evolved into the industry leader, later expanding into other forms of vessel, including the iconic World War II [[PT boat]].\n\nIn the early part of the 20th century electric propulsion was adapted to use in [[submarine]]s. As underwater propulsion driven exclusively by heavy batteries was both slow and of limited range and timespan, rechargeable battery banks were developed.  Submarines were primarily powered by combined [[diesel-electric]] systems on the surface, which were much faster and allowed for dramatically expanded range, charging their battery systems as necessary for still limited subsurface action and duration. The [[Plunger (experimental submarine)|Holland V]] submarine led to the adoption of this system by the [[U.S. Navy]], followed by the [[British Royal Navy]].\n\nTo expand the range and duration of the submarine during World War II the German [[Kriegsmarine]] developed a [[Submarine snorkel|snorkel]] system, which allowed the diesel-electric system to be utilized while the submarine was all but completely submerged. Finally, in 1952, the [[USS Nautilus (SSN-571)|USS ''Nautilus'']] was launched, the world's first nuclear powered submarine, which eliminated the restrictions of both diesel fuel and limited duration battery propulsion.\n\n[[Electric boat#List of battery-electric ships|Several short-range ships are built as (or converted to) pure electric vessels]]. This includes some powered by batteries which are recharged from shore, and some [[shore-power]]ed by [[Electric boat#Wired electric boats|electrical cables]], [[Straussee Ferry|either]] [[Canby Ferry|overhead]] or [[Kastellet ferry|submerged]] (no batteries).\n\nOn November 12, 2017 [[Guangzhou Shipyard International]] (GSI) launched what may be the world's first all-electric, battery-powered inland coal carrier. The 2,000 dwt vessel will carry bulk cargo for up to 40 nautical miles per charge. The ship carries [[lithium ion batteries]] rated at 2,400 kilowatt-hours, about the same amount as 30 [[Tesla Model S]] electric sedans.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://maritime-executive.com/article/chinese-yard-launches-battery-powered-coal-carrier |title=Chinese Yard Launches Battery-Powered Coal Carrier |url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171115020231/https://www.maritime-executive.com/article/chinese-yard-launches-battery-powered-coal-carrier |archivedate=2017-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/china-launches-world-s-first-fully-electric-cargo-ship/story-ceg5ZbMb67yOLpYFZNdg4I.html |title=China launches world\u2019s first fully electric cargo ship|date=14 November 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20171115143658/http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/china-launches-world-s-first-fully-electric-cargo-ship/story-ceg5ZbMb67yOLpYFZNdg4I.html |archivedate=15 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Propulsion types==\nNumerous types of propulsion have been developed over time. These include:\n\n===Propeller===\n{{Main|Propeller}}\nMarine propellers are also known as \"screws\". There are many variations of marine screw systems, including twin, contra-rotating, controllable-pitch, and nozzle-style screws.  While smaller vessels tend to have a single screw, even very large ships such as tankers, container ships and bulk carriers may have single screws for reasons of fuel efficiency.  Other vessels may have twin, triple or quadruple screws.  Power is transmitted from the engine to the screw by way of a propeller shaft, which may be connected to a gearbox.\n\n===Paddle wheel===\n[[File:Paddle wheel small.jpg|thumb|left|Left: original paddle wheel from a paddle steamer.<br>Right: detail of a paddle steamer.]]\n{{See also|Paddle steamer|Pedalo}}\nThe paddle wheel is a large wheel, generally built of a [[steel frame]]work, upon the outer edge of which are fitted numerous paddle blades (called ''floats'' or ''buckets'').  The bottom quarter or so of the wheel travels underwater.  Rotation of the paddle wheel produces [[thrust]], forward or backward as required.  More advanced paddle wheel designs have featured ''feathering'' methods that keep each paddle blade oriented closer to vertical while it is in the water; this increases efficiency.  The upper part of a paddle wheel is normally enclosed in a paddlebox to minimise splashing.\n\nPaddle wheels have been superseded by screws, which are a much more efficient form of propulsion.  Nevertheless, paddle wheels have two advantages over screws, making them suitable for vessels in  shallow rivers and constrained waters: first, they are less likely to be clogged by obstacles and debris; and secondly, when contra-rotating, they allow the vessel to spin around its own vertical axis.  Some vessels had a single screw in addition to two paddle wheels, to gain the advantages of both types of propulsion.\n\n===Pump jet===\n{{main|pump-jet}}\nA '''pump-jet''', '''hydrojet''', '''water jet''', or '''jet drive''' uses a [[ducted propeller]] ([[axial-flow pump]]), [[centrifugal pump]], or mixed flow pump to create a jet of water for propulsion.\n\nThese incorporate an intake for source water and a nozzle to direct its flow out, generating momentum, and in most cases, employing thrust vectoring to steer the craft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hamiltonmarine.co.nz/includes/files_cms/file/JetTorque%2008.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-10-29 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120110527/http://hamiltonmarine.co.nz/includes/files_cms/file/JetTorque%2008.pdf |archivedate=2018-01-20 }}</ref>\n\nPump-jets are found on [[personal watercraft]], shallow-draft river boats, and torpedoes.\n\n===Sail===\n{{main|Forces on sails}}\nThe purpose of [[sail]]s is to use [[wind]] [[energy]] to propel the [[sailboat|vessel]], [[ice boat|sled]], [[sailboard|board]], [[land sailing|vehicle]] or  [[windmill sail|rotor]].\n\n===Voith-Schneider cyclo-rotor===\n[[Image:VSPreal.jpg|right|thumb|100px|Voith Schneider Propeller]]\nA [[Voith Schneider Propeller]] (VSP) is a practical [[cyclorotor]] that provides instant thrust in any direction. There is no need to turn a propulsor. Most ships with VSPs do not need or have a rudder. VSPs are often used in tugboats, drilling vessels, and other watercraft that require unusually good maneuverability. First deployed in the 1930s, Voith-Schneider drives are both reliable and available in large sizes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://voith.com/corp-en/drives-transmissions/voith-schneider-propeller-vsp.html |publisher=Voith Global GMBH |accessdate=10 November 2019 |title=Voith Schneider Propeller VSP}}</ref>\n\n===Caterpillar===\n[[File:Popular Science Dec 1918 p68 - History of boat propulsion, Water caterpillar.jpg|thumb|right|The water caterpillar boat propulsion system ([[Popular Science]] Monthly, December 1918)]]\nAn early uncommon means of boat propulsion was the water caterpillar.  This moved a series of paddles on chains along the bottom of the boat to propel it over the water and preceded the development of [[tracked vehicle]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Caterpillar Is Now Being Applied to Ships|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EikDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA68|date=December 1918|publisher=Popular Science|page=68}}</ref> The first water caterpillar was developed by [[:de:Joseph-Philibert Desblanc|Joseph-Philibert Desblanc]] in 1782 and propelled by a steam engine. In the United States the first water caterpillar was patented in 1839 by William Leavenworth of New York.{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}\n\n==Buoyancy==\n[[Underwater gliders]] convert buoyancy to thrust, using wings, or more recently hull shape (SeaExplorer Glider). Buoyancy is made alternatively negative and positive, generating tooth-saw profiles.\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n*{{annotated link|Air-independent propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Astern propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Combined nuclear and steam propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Diesel generator}}\n*{{annotated link|Experiment (horse-powered boat)|''Experiment'' (horse-powered boat)}}\n*{{annotated link|Integrated electric propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Internal drive propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Non-road engine}}\n*{{annotated link|Nuclear marine propulsion}}\n*{{annotated link|Wind-assisted propulsion}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category}}\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marine Propulsion}}\n[[Category:Marine propulsion]]\n", "name_user": "HopsonRoad"